<BLOCK1><TI>NOTICE OF APPLICATION FOR LEAVE TO APPEAL</TI>
<P>Take notice that Gize Yebeyo Araya, Kesete Tekle Fshazion and Mihretab Yemane Tekle, the Appellants, hereby apply for leave to appeal to the Court of Appeal for British Columbia from the order of The Honourable Mr. Justice Abrioux of the Supreme Court of British Columbia, pronounced the 18th day of January, 2019, at Vancouver, British Columbia.</P>
<P>1. The appeal is from a:
<P1>&square; Trial Judgment</P1>
<P1>&square; Order of a Statutory Body</P1>
<P1>&square; Summary Trial Judgment</P1>
<P1>&timesb; Chambers Judgment</P1></P>
<P>2. If the appeal is from an appeal under Rule 18-3 or 23-6 (8) of the Supreme Court Civil Rules or Rule 18-3 or 22-7 (8) of the Supreme Court Family Rules, name the maker of the original decision, direction or order: N/A</P>
<P>3. Please identify which of the following is involved in the appeal:
<P1>&square; Constitutional/Administrative</P1>
<P1>&timesb; Civil Procedure</P1>
<P1>&square; Commercial</P1>
<P1>&square; Family</P1>
<P1>&square; Motor Vehicle Accidents</P1>
<P1>&square; Municipal Law</P1>
<P1>&square; Real Property</P1>
<P1>&square; Torts</P1>
<P1>&square; Equity</P1>
<P1>&square; Wills and Estates</P1></P>
<P>And further take notice that the Court of Appeal will be moved at the hearing of this application for an order that:</P>
<P>1. this Notice of Application for Leave to Appeal stands as a Notice of Appeal of the order of Mr. Justice Abrioux of the Supreme Court of British Columbia, pronounced the 18th day of January, 2019, in which his Lordship granted, in part, the Defendant's application regarding waiver of privilege (the &ldquo;Order&rdquo;);</P>
<P>2. alternatively, if leave to appeal is required, that leave be given to appeal the Order;</P>
<P>3. the appeal be allowed and the Order be set aside;</P>
<P>4. the appellants have costs of this appeal; and</P>
<P>5. such further and other relief be granted as to this Honourable Court seems just.</P>
<P>The grounds of appeal are:</P>
<P>1. the Honourable Mr. Justice Abrioux erred in law or principle by finding that the plaintiffs in each of the related actions, other than the Araya Action, have, by pleading postponement, waived privilege over communications and documents relating to the first meeting between each plaintiff and Canadian counsel;</P>
<P>2. further or alternatively, even if the plaintiffs in each of the related actions, other than the Araya Action, have waived privilege over some communications and documents relating to the first meeting between each plaintiff and Canadian counsel, the Honourable Mr. Justice Abrioux erred by ordering broader production of privileged documents and communications than what is necessary to achieve a just result; and</P>
<P>3. further or alternatively, the Honourable Mr. Justice Abrioux erred in law or principle by ordering that the plaintiffs in the related actions shall produce documents relating to or containing the particulars of the retainer or engagement of Ms. Elsa Chyrum by their counsel within 45 days of the date of the Order.</P>
<P>The hearing of this proceeding occupied 2 days.</P>
<P>Dated at Vancouver, British Columbia, this 8th day of February, 2019.</P>
<P>&ellip35; Solicitor for the Appellants</P>
<P>Joe Fiorante, Q.C.</P>
