<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="II">OPENING STATEMENT</TI>
<P>The plaintiffs are all refugees who have fled Eritrea. They appeal the chambers judge's declaration that, by pleading that any applicable limitation periods were postponed until they had access to the Canadian legal counsel necessary to discover their claims, they have implicitly waived privilege over all communications and documents relating to their first meeting with Canadian counsel. They also appeal the chambers judge's order that they produce documents setting out the particulars of their counsel's engagement of Ms. Elizabeth Chyrum, who is retained by counsel to communicate with the plaintiffs in relation to the litigation. Although the appeal arises out of a pre-trial application brought by the defendant, Nevsun Resources Ltd. (&ldquo;Nevsun&rdquo;), the jurisdictional basis for the chambers judge's declaration was his inherent jurisdiction, not the provisions of the <EM>Supreme Court Civil Rules</EM> that govern the pre-trial discovery process.</P>
<P>The chambers judge erred in his approach to assessing whether the pleadings led to a waiver of solicitor-client privilege over the documents and communications relating to each of the plaintiffs' first meeting with Canadian counsel. Specifically, he erred in not considering whether, through the pleadings, the plaintiffs had relied on legal advice that might have been communicated at those first meetings. Any legal advice conveyed at these meetings is irrelevant to the ultimate task of assessing whether the plaintiffs' claims were discoverable before the date upon which they each first met Canadian counsel and had access to Canadian legal advice. The chambers judge therefore erred in granting a declaration of waiver of privilege over communications relating to the plaintiffs' first meeting with Canadian counsel. Alternatively, the scope of the declaration is overly broad.</P>
<P>In addition, the chambers judge also erred by ordering the plaintiffs to produce documents relating to the particulars of Ms. Chyrum's retainer. These documents would normally be covered by litigation privilege. However, the plaintiffs had no opportunity to establish the privilege and the chambers judge failed to consider the principles of litigation privilege when ordering their production. This too was an error.</P></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="III">PART 1&mdash;STATEMENT OF FACTS</TI>
<BLOCK2><N><EM>1)</EM></N><TI><EM>Background</EM></TI>
<BLOCK3><N>a)</N><TI><UNDER>The Related Actions</UNDER></TI>
<P>1. The plaintiffs in the underlying related actions allege that Nevsun entered into a commercial venture with the Government of Eritrea to develop the Bisha mine in Eritrea. They allege that they were forced to work on the mine's construction under the constant threat of physical punishment, torture and imprisonment. The plaintiffs allege that Nevsun was complicit in the use of forced labour, slavery, torture, inhuman treatment and crimes against humanity.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Araya v. Nevsun Resources</SOC><CITE>2017 BCCA 401</CITE><PARANUM>1&ndash;7</PARANUM></CASEREF> (&ldquo;<EM>Araya Appeal</EM>&rdquo;) leave granted <CASEREF><CITE>2018 CanLII 53456</CITE><COURTJUR>SCC</COURTJUR></CASEREF> (currently under reserve).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>2. The first of the related actions, <CASEREF><SOC>Araya et al. v. Nevsun Resources Ltd.</SOC><DOCKET>SCBC Vancouver Registry No. S-148932</DOCKET></CASEREF> (&ldquo;Araya Action&rdquo;), was originally framed as a proposed representative proceeding. After the chambers judge granted Nevsun's application challenging this form of proceeding in 2016,<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>See <CASEREF><SOC>Araya v. Nevsun Resources</SOC><CITE>2016 BCSC 1856</CITE><PARANUM>486&ndash;570</PARANUM></CASEREF> (&ldquo;<EM>Araya 2016</EM>&rdquo;) aff'd on other grounds <CASEREF><CITE>2017 BCCA 401</CITE><CASEHIST><CASEDISP>leave granted</CASEDISP><CASEREF><CITE>2018 CanLII 53456</CITE><COURTJUR>SCC</COURTJUR></CASEREF></CASEHIST></CASEREF>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> however, nine additional related actions were filed and served. There are currently ten actions involving over 80 plaintiffs under common judicial management (the &ldquo;Related Actions&rdquo;).<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Araya v. Nevsun Resources</SOC><CITE>2019 BCCA 104</CITE><PARANUM>1</PARANUM></CASEREF> (&ldquo;<EM>Araya Leave</EM>&rdquo;).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Until his recent appointment to this Court, Mr. Justice Abrioux was designated as the common judicial management judge for the actions.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Reasons for Judgment of Mr. Justice Abrioux (&ldquo;Reasons&rdquo;), at para 2, Appeal Record (&ldquo;AR&rdquo;), Tab 16, p. 154.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>3. A six month trial is currently scheduled to begin in 2020.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Reasons at para 10, AR, Tab 16, p. 155.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> A bellwether application, which will decide whether the trial will proceed by way of test cases, is set to be heard later this year.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Reasons at para 12, AR, Tab 16, p. 155.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>b)</N><TI><UNDER>The Pleas of Postponement</UNDER></TI>
<P>4. In its responses to civil claim, Nevsun asserts as a defence the expiration of the applicable limitation period, either under Eritrean law, or in the alternative, under the <EM>Limitation Act</EM>.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Limitation Act</EM>, SBC 2012, c 13.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> In reply, the plaintiffs have pleaded that the actions are not subject to any limitation period. In the alternative, however, the plaintiffs plead that any applicable limitation period was postponed until at least the time when each of the plaintiffs accessed the legal advice of Canadian counsel necessary to ascertain and assess their legal rights in Canada against Nevsun.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>See e.g., Reply at para 1 in <CASEREF><SOC>Alemayo v. Nevsun Resources Ltd.</SOC><DOCKET>SCBC Action No. S169522</DOCKET></CASEREF>, filed February 9, 2018, AR, Tabs 4&ndash;12 (&ldquo;Replies&rdquo;).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>5. The plaintiffs plead that before their first meeting with Canadian counsel, they lacked the means to discover that a court action in British Columbia was an appropriate way to seek a remedy against Nevsun.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>See e.g. Amended Reply at paras 8&ndash;11 in <CASEREF><SOC>Negash et al v. Nevsun Resources Ltd.</SOC><DOCKET>SCBC Action No. S-1610863</DOCKET></CASEREF>, filed February 13, 2018, AR, Tab 9, p. 79.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Under s. 8 of the <EM>Limitation Act</EM>, the plaintiffs' claims are not discoverable until they knew or reasonably ought to have known the necessary material facts and that a court proceeding against Nevsun would be an appropriate means to seek a remedy for their injuries.</P>
<P>6. Following delivery of the replies, Nevsun brought an application alleging that by pleading postponement, the plaintiffs in each of the Related Actions had implicitly waived privilege over all communications and documents relating to the pursuit of the actions up until the date that each of the claims were filed.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Nevsun's Notice of Application, at para 1, AR, Tab 13, pp. 128-129.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> At the hearing, Nevsun narrowed its allegations of waiver due to postponement, other than in the Araya Action, to the time period leading up to, and including, the plaintiffs' first meeting with Canadian counsel.</P>
<P>7. Since Nevsun first raised the issue of waiver of privilege, the plaintiffs have not disputed that the postponement pleadings put in issue the plaintiffs' state of mind regarding the extent to which they had knowledge of the core ingredients of the lawsuit prior to their first meeting with Canadian counsel.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Affidavit #8 of Roxanne Dhanpaul, sworn December 12, 2018 (&ldquo;Dhanpaul #8&rdquo;), Exhibits M and N, Appellants' Appeal Book (&ldquo;AB&rdquo;), Tab 1.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>c)</N><TI><UNDER>Application for Production of Third Party Communications</UNDER></TI>
<P>8. In addition to the application for a declaration that solicitor-client privilege had been waived due to the postponement pleadings, Nevsun sought a declaration that no litigation or solicitor-client privilege attached to all communications between and amongst the plaintiffs and Ms. Chyrum and other third parties involved in the coordination and pursuit of the Related Actions.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Nevsun's Notice of Application at para 4, AR, Tab 13, p. 129.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Alternatively, Nevsun sought a declaration that the plaintiffs had waived privilege over these documents.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Nevsun's Notice of Application at para 5, AR, Tab 13, p. 129.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> On examinations for discovery, counsel for the plaintiffs had objected to questions concerning communications between Ms. Chyrum and the plaintiffs following their initial meeting with counsel on the basis of solicitor-client and litigation privilege.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>See e.g. Affidavit #9 of Roxanne Dhanpaul, filed April 15, 2019 (&ldquo;Dhanpaul #9&rdquo;), Exhibit A at Q765, AB, Tab 3.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>9. In their responding materials, the plaintiffs provided evidence that Ms. Chyrum is an agent of counsel who is retained to communicate with clients, witnesses and potential clients.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Affidavit #9 of Kimberly Hill, made December 21, 2018 (&ldquo;Hill #9&rdquo;), at para 4, 2; Affidavit#1 of Dimitri Lascaris, made December 21, 2018, at para 3, AB, Tab 4.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><N><EM>2)</EM></N><TI><EM>Reasons of the Chambers Judge</EM></TI>
<BLOCK3><N>a)</N><TI><UNDER>Reasons on Waiver of Privilege</UNDER></TI>
<P>10. In oral reasons, later released in writing, the chambers judge granted Nevsun's application in part. The chambers judge declared that by pleading postponement, the plaintiffs had &ldquo;waived privilege over all communications and documents, in any way relating to the pursuit of the Actions or the claims advanced therein, by reason of the plea of postponement asserted in the reply&rdquo;.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Order Made After Application of Mr. Justice Abrioux, entered February 21, 2019 (&ldquo;Order&rdquo;) para 2, AR, Tab 15, p. 149.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>11. For the plaintiffs in the Related Actions other than the Araya Action, the chambers judge found that the waiver extended to the date upon which each of the plaintiffs met Canadian counsel for the first time, and included all documents (other than retainer agreements) prepared in contemplation of, or which record or refer to what occurred at these first meetings.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Reasons at paras 112-113, AR, Tab 16, pp. 177-178.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The chambers judge concluded that the waiver should include what occurred at the first meeting with counsel &ldquo;since it could only be as a result of the meeting that the plaintiffs' state of mind would have transitioned from one of without knowledge or certainty to that of was a reasonable likelihood of success against Nevsun in a Canadian court.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Reasons at para 90, AR, Tab 16, pp. 173-174.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> On this point, the chambers judge relied on a 2014 journal article by an Ontario lawyer, Jonathan de Vries, in which Mr. de Vries argues that the a plea that the limitation period has been postponed should give rise to an implied waiver of privilege over solicitor-client communications that at least extends up to and includes the putative discovery date so that the &ldquo;paradigm shift&rdquo; in the plaintiff's state of knowledge of a claim can be tested by the defendant.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Reasons at paras 80 and 90, AR, Tab 16, pp. 171&ndash;174; Jonathan de Vries, &ldquo;Privilege and Limitations: The Impact of Raising the Discoverability of Claims on Solicitor-Client Privilege&rdquo;, (2014) 43 Advocates Quarterly 219&ndash;256 (&ldquo;de Vries&rdquo;) at 252.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>12. As the plaintiffs indicated that they intended to apply to amend the pleadings in the Araya Action, the chambers judge adjourned Nevsun's application in relation to that action. The chambers judge ordered the plaintiffs to produce the documents over which privilege had been waived within 45 days of the date of the order.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Reasons at para 112, AR, Tab 16, pp. 177-178.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>b)</N><TI><UNDER>Production of the Particulars of Ms. Chyrum's Retainer</UNDER></TI>
<P>13. Before the chambers judge, Nevsun narrowed its request for a broad declaration that no privilege attached to all communications between Ms. Chyrum and the plaintiffs to one based on specific objections for solicitor-client and litigation privilege made by the plaintiffs' counsel at examinations for discovery.</P>
<P>14. Nevsun also took significant issue with the evidence that Ms. Chyrum was an agent of counsel retained to communicate with clients and potential clients because Ms. Chyrum had also previously served as a translator on some of the plaintiffs' affidavits. None of these affidavits were at issue on this application. Nevsun had previously alleged that Ms. Chyrum's translations raised a spectre of bias in the context of a 2016 application, which the chambers judge had rejected.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Araya 2016</EM> at paras 216-217.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>15. Nevsun had not requested production of Ms. Chyrum's affidavit in its notice of application and nor did it apply for production of Ms. Chyrum's retainer at the hearing. Nevertheless, the chambers judge ordered that the particulars of Ms. Chyrum's retainer agreement with Canadian counsel be disclosed.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Reasons at para 109, AR, Tab 16, p. 177.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The chambers judge found that production of the particulars of her retainer agreement &ldquo;may well assist in delineating Ms. Chyrum's precise role while acting as a third party agent for counsel and/or be material to any potential allegations of bias arising from her translator and interpreter functions.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Reasons at para 109, AR, Tab 16, p. 177.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>16. The chambers judge declined to make specific rulings on the objections at the examinations for discovery. He left it to counsel to determine the validity of the objections based on his reasons concerning waiver of privilege and granted the parties leave to make further submissions on any unresolved issues.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Reasons at paras 110-111, AR, Tab 16, p. 177.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><N><EM>3)</EM></N><TI><EM>Leave to Appeal not Required</EM></TI>
<P>17. The parties appeared before Mr. Justice Butler on March 18, 2019 on the plaintiffs' application for an order directing that leave to appeal was not required, or alternatively, an order granting leave to appeal. Mr. Justice Butler granted the plaintiffs' application. He reasoned that as the jurisdictional basis of the declaration was the Court's inherent jurisdiction, leave to appeal was not required.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Araya Leave</EM> at paras 25-26.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Had leave to appeal been required, he found that the test for leave had been met in any event.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Araya Leave</EM> at para 27.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> He also ordered that execution of the order be stayed pending disposition of this appeal.</P></BLOCK2></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="IV">PART 2&mdash;ERRORS IN JUDGMENT</TI>
<P>18. The plaintiffs submit that the chambers judge erred as follows:
<P1>(a) by declaring that the plaintiffs had waived solicitor-client privilege over communications relating to their first meeting with Canadian counsel when the plaintiffs do not put legal advice that may have been received at these meetings at issue;</P1>
<P1>(b) alternatively, even if there was an implicit waiver of privilege, the chambers judge erred by making a broad declaration of waiver not limited to the issue of whether the plaintiffs knew or ought to have known prior to meeting Canadian counsel that an action against Nevsun in Canada would be appropriate; and</P1>
<P1>(c) further, the chambers judge erred by ordering the production of litigation privileged communications concerning the particulars of Ms. Chyrum's retainer.</P1></P>
<P>19. Each of these issues are reviewable on a standard of correctness. The first two issues involves questions concerning the identification and application of the test for implied waiver of privilege. This is a question of law reviewable on a correctness standard.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Soprema Inc. v. Wolrige Mahon LLP</SOC><CITE>2016 BCCA 471</CITE><PARANUM>16</PARANUM></CASEREF> (&ldquo;<EM>Soprema</EM>&rdquo;).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The third ground of appeal involves an extricable error in principle concerning whether the chambers judge applied the correct principles of law when considering whether Ms. Chyrum's retainer should be produced.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Ledcor Construction Ltd. v. North bridge Indemnity Insurance Co.</SOC><CITE>2016 SCC 37</CITE><PARANUM>36</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="V">PART 3&mdash;ARGUMENT</TI>
<BLOCK2><N><EM>1)</EM></N><TI><EM>The Postponement Pleadings Do Not Implicitly Waive Privilege</EM></TI>
<BLOCK3><N>a)</N><TI><UNDER>Declarations of Waiver of Privilege are Discouraged</UNDER></TI>
<P>20. The order below declares that the plaintiffs have waived privilege over a broad swath of documents and communications up to and including the date upon which each of the plaintiffs first met Canadian counsel.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Order at para 2, AR, Tab 15, p. 149.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Instead of challenging specific objections at examinations for discovery or claims of privilege over specific documents, Nevsun applied for a broad and general declaration that applies across ten related actions and the claims of over eighty plaintiffs. The jurisdictional basis of the order was the chambers judge's inherent jurisdiction, not the provisions of the <EM>Supreme Court Civil Rules</EM> that govern the pre-trial discovery process.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Araya Leave</EM> at para 15.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>21. In <CASEREF><SOC>H.M.B. Holdings Limited v. Replay Resorts Inc.</SOC></CASEREF>, this Court recently disapproved of a similar approach to that taken by Nevsun here. Like Nevsun, the respondents in <EM>HMB</EM> sought a broad declaration not tied to particular documents or questions on discovery. Writing for the Court, Justice Hunter reasoned that such an approach was only appropriate in rare circumstances.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>H.M.B. Holdings Limited v. Replay Resorts Inc.</SOC><CITE>2018 BCCA 263</CITE></CASEREF> (&ldquo;<EM>HMB</EM>&rdquo;) at para 36 leave to appeal dismissed <CASEREF><CITE>2019 CanLII 18828</CITE></CASEREF>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> He noted that while declarations of privilege are within the court's inherent jurisdiction to make, the practice of challenging privilege in this way &ldquo;enhances the danger that a waiver order will be made in circumstances that do not adequately protect the privilege.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>HMB</EM> at para 33.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>22. This danger was realized once again here. As Justice Butler noted, Nevsun's application cast &ldquo;a very broad net and the declaration in the Order is similarly broad.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Araya Leave</EM> at para 21.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Although the chambers judge referred in passing to the &ldquo;virtually sacrosanct status&rdquo; of solicitor-client privilege, the order does not give appropriate attention to the high, bright-line bar this Court has set for findings of implicit waiver of solicitor-client privilege.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Soprema</EM> at para 51.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> As discussed in further detail below, Nevsun's decision to proceed in this way led to a very broad order that applies generally in the litigation and that is not tailored to the particular circumstances of each plaintiff or limited to particular documents or questions on discovery.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>b)</N><TI><UNDER>The Chambers Judge Applied the Wrong Test</UNDER></TI>
<P>23. In <EM>Soprema</EM>, this Court was clear that a pleading that invokes a party's &ldquo;state of mind&rdquo; is insufficient to ground a waiver of privilege.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Soprema</EM> at paras 48-49, 52; see also <EM>HMB</EM> at paras 44 and 46.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> After extensively reviewing the case law and applicable principles, Justice Harris concluded that to waive privilege &ldquo;a party must voluntarily inject into the litigation legal advice it received or its understanding of the law&rdquo;.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Soprema</EM> at para 49.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The fact that legal advice may be relevant to or may have influenced the party's state of mind is insufficient.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Soprema</EM> at para 52.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>24. In <EM>HMB</EM>, Justice Hunter further clarified that for a party to have put its understanding of the law at issue more &ldquo;than a statement of a litigant's understanding of the law&rdquo; is required.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>HMB</EM> at para 46.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Even an admission by a party that he or she relied on legal advice is insufficient.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Sopinka, Lederman &amp; Bryant: The Law of Evidence in Canada</EM>, 5th ed. (Toronto: LexisNexis Canada, 2018) at &sect;14.159 (&ldquo;<EM>Sopinka</EM>&rdquo;), cited in <EM>HMB</EM> at para 43.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Implied waiver requires pleadings, evidence or argument that asserts actual reliance on the legal advice.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>HMB</EM> at paras 46-47.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>25. In a passage cited favourably in <EM>HMB</EM>, the authors of <EM>Sopinka, Lederman &amp; Bryant: The Law of Evidence in Canada</EM>, 5th ed., state that waiver requires a party to have chosen &ldquo;to use the legal advice as a substantive element of his or her claim or defence.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Sopinka</EM> at &sect;14.159 quoting <CASEREF><SOC>Creative Career Systems Inc. v. Ontario</SOC><CITE>2012 ONSC 649</CITE><PARANUM>31</PARANUM></CASEREF> (<EM>&ldquo;Creative Career Stystems&rdquo;</EM>), cited in <EM>HMB</EM> at para 43.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>26. In <CASEREF><SOC>Mickelson v. Borden Ladner Gervais LLP</SOC></CASEREF>, Justice Iyer helpfully reformulated the principles set out in <EM>Soprema</EM> into the following three requirements, all of which must be established before solicitor-client privilege is implicitly waived:
<P1>(a) the state of mind of the party asserting the privilege is an element of a claim or defence;</P1>
<P1>(b) the party asserting the privilege is known to have received legal advice relating to that issue; and</P1>
<P1>(c) the party asserting the privilege is relying on the legal advice to justify its conduct.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Mickelson v. Borden Ladner Gervais LLP</SOC><CITE>2017 BCSC 1584</CITE><PARANUM>18</PARANUM></CASEREF>; see also <CASEREF><SOC>Turner Lane Development Corporation v. Levelton Consultants Ltd.</SOC><CITE>2017 BCSC 1940</CITE><PARANUM>22</PARANUM></CASEREF>, where Master Bouck reformulated the same requirements into a three-part test.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P1></P>
<P>27. The common thread in this recent case law is that waiver of privilege requires a party to have voluntarily injected legal advice or its understanding of the law into the litigation by relying on legal advice as a justification or explanation for its conduct.</P>
<P>28. Instead of applying these principles, the chambers judge relied on Nevsun's submission for the proposition that &ldquo;[a] party waives privilege where he puts his state of mind at issue with respect to legal knowledge in the litigation.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Reasons at paras 72-73, AR, Tab 16, p. 170; See Nevsun's Notice of Application, para 2, AR, Tab 13, p. 129.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> This proposition is consistent with statements found in earlier authority such as <CASEREF><SOC>Camosun College v. Levelton Engineering Ltd.</SOC></CASEREF>,<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Camosun College v. Levelton Engineering Ltd.</SOC><CITE>2014 BCSC 1190</CITE><PARANUM>13</PARANUM></CASEREF> (<EM>&ldquo;Camosun College&rdquo;</EM>).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> however, without further explanation it is incomplete. Without the further stipulation that waiver requires a party to have <UNDER>relied</UNDER> on legal advice to justify its conduct, the statement is inconsistent with <EM>Soprema</EM> and <EM>HMB</EM>. The proposition resembles the reasoning of the trial judge in <EM>Soprema</EM>, who found that implicit waiver may occur if a party puts &ldquo;its &ldquo;state of mind&rdquo; in issue in a manner establishing a clear nexus between its state of mind and the privileged communications.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Soprema</EM> at para 3.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> As Justice Harris concluded, this is insufficient to establish waiver.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Soprema</EM> at paras 3-4.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> For waiver to be implied, a party must have voluntarily injected the legal advice or its understanding of law into the litigation by relying on legal advice.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Soprema</EM> at para 49; <EM>HMB</EM> at paras 46-47.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>29. By basing his analysis on an incomplete statement of the law on waiver of privilege, the chambers judge considered the wrong factors when he assessed whether the plaintiffs had waived privilege over their first meeting with Canadian counsel. Nowhere in his reasons did the chambers judge consider whether the plaintiffs rely on the legal advice they may have received upon their first meeting with Canadian counsel. Instead, the chambers judge's reasons are focused on assessing the potential relevancy of legal advice to the question of discoverability and the pleading of postponement.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Reasons at paras 74 and 90, AR, Tab 16, pp. 170 and 173-174.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>30. Also, while the plaintiffs acknowledge that the pleadings put their states of mind before meeting with Canadian counsel at issue, it is not clear whether any of the plaintiffs received legal advice on the possibility of legal action against Nevsun prior to first meeting Canadian counsel. This reemphasizes the dangers inherent in the procedure Nevsun followed below. The broad declaration it sought does not allow for the individualized inquiry the waiver of privilege assessment calls for.</P>
<P>31. In many ways, the chambers judge's approach is similar to that taken by the chambers judge in <EM>HMB</EM>, which was rejected by this Court. In that case, the chambers judge had accepted the theory that when the plaintiffs &ldquo;asserted that they filed the Conspiracy Claim when the did because of a concern about a limitation period, they must have had legal advice on that subject, and the reference to limitation periods constituted a waiver of the legal advice received by them.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>HMB</EM> at para 39.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>32. The reasons at issue here make a similar speculative leap. The chambers judge's finding of a waiver of privilege over the first meeting with counsel is based on his conclusion that &ldquo;it could only be as a result of the meeting that the plaintiffs' state of mind would have transitioned from one of without knowledge or certainty to that of was a reasonable likelihood of success against Nevsun in a Canadian court.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Reasons at para 90, AR, Tab 16, pp. 173-174.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> In effect, the chambers judge assumed that the privileged communications that occurred at that meeting were relevant to assessing the plaintiffs' pleas of postponement.</P>
<P>33. That this speculation was necessary demonstrates that the plaintiffs' reply pleadings do not inject the legal advice they may have received at these meetings into the litigation. The plaintiffs do not plead that legal advice they received at their first meetings with Canadian counsel was what made their claims against Nevsun discoverable. Instead, the plaintiffs plead that it was the <UNDER>access to</UNDER> legal advice from Canadian counsel that allowed them to discover that a claim against Nevsun in Canada would be appropriate.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>c)</N><TI><UNDER>The Reply Pleadings Do Not Rely on Legal Advice Received at the First Meetings</UNDER></TI>
<P>34. The pleadings themselves do not incorporate any legal advice that may have been communicated at these meetings as a substantive element of the plaintiffs' reply. In pleading that any applicable limitation period was postponed &ldquo;until at least the time when they accessed the legal advice of Canadian counsel necessary to ascertain and assess their legal rights in Canada&rdquo;,<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>See e.g. Reply at para 8 in <CASEREF><SOC>Mekonen v. Nevsun Resources Ltd.</SOC><DOCKET>SCBC Action No. S-184108</DOCKET></CASEREF>, filed May 25, 2018, AR, Tab 11, p. 108.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> the plaintiffs do not inject any legal advice that may have been received at these meetings as an issue in the litigation. While the passage references legal advice, the pleadings do not incorporate that legal advice as part of their pleas of postponement. The reply pleadings make the point that the plaintiffs were unable to bring the action until they had access to lawyers willing and able to represent them. Access to legal advice is a pleaded precursor to the discovery of the claims, but legal advice is not the basis for the postponement plea.</P>
<P>35. Similarly, the other references in the reply pleadings to legal advice do not put the plaintiffs' possible reliance on that legal advice into issue. For example, in evaluating whether the &ldquo;plaintiffs' claims against Nevsun involve complex and novel issues of domestic tort law and customary international law&rdquo; it is not necessary to assess the plaintiffs' state of mind. The issue of whether the action is complex is a question for the court to decide. Legal advice the plaintiffs may have received on this issue upon first meeting with Canadian counsel is irrelevant to that assessment.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>See <EM>Creative Career Systems</EM> at para 33: &ldquo;Similarly, it is irrelevant to the lawsuit that the Plaintiffs may have obtained legal advice to support their assertion that they owned the private career colleges. Ultimately, the court will decide the ownership issue based on facts that do not include either party's lawyer's legal opinion about ownership.&rdquo;</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>36. That the plaintiffs do not rely on the legal advice communicated at these first meetings is demonstrated by the fact that the content of any legal advice that may have been provided is irrelevant to assessing the strength of the plaintiffs' pleas of postponement. No matter what advice they received during the first meeting, the communications do not shed light on whether the plaintiffs could have discovered earlier that a court action in British Columbia was an appropriate means of proceeding. Whether counsel told the plaintiffs at these meetings that a case against Nevsun in British Columbia had a strong chance, a weak chance or no chance of success at all, it makes no difference when assessing whether the plaintiffs could have discovered the claims any earlier than the day on which they first met with Canadian counsel. In the absence of relevancy, it is difficult to see how the pleadings put in issue the plaintiffs' reliance on these communications.</P>
<P>37. The only portion of the privileged communications that occurred at the first meetings that could possibly be relevant to assessing the plaintiffs' claims of postponement is information from the plaintiffs about what steps they previously took to seek legal redress or the knowledge they had about the lawsuit before the meeting.</P>
<P>38. However, Nevsun does not require access to the plaintiffs' legal file to investigate and inquire about these issues. The plaintiffs have always acknowledged that the postponement pleadings put into issue the plaintiffs' state of mind regarding the extent to which they had knowledge of the core ingredients of the lawsuit prior to first meeting Canadian counsel.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Dhanpaul #8, Exhibits M and N, AB, Tab 1.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Nevsun has explored these issues on discovery.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>See e.g. Dhanpaul #9, Exhibit A at Q 736&ndash;762, AB, Tab 3.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>39. Further, and more fundamentally, relevancy does not drive waiver of privilege.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Soprema</EM> at para 52.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> While preventing Nevsun from accessing privileged communications relating to these first meeting might deny Nevsun access to some potentially relevant material concerning what occurred before the plaintiffs first met with Canadian counsel, this is an appropriate consequence of the fair recognition of solicitor-client privilege. On this issue, Justice Harris's reasons in <EM>Soprema</EM> are squarely on point:
<QUOTE><P>I do not think one can properly describe a litigation advantage &ldquo;unfair&rdquo; when it results from the recognition and protection of a fundamentally important principle in the legal system. Furthermore, protecting privilege in these circumstances does not raise an issue of inconsistency because the party asserting the privilege is not relying on the advice it received to justify its conduct at the same time as it shields that advice from disclosure.</P>
<P><EM>(Soprema</EM> at para 53)</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>40. Here, the plaintiffs do not rely on the legal advice they may have received at their first meetings with Canadian counsel as a justification for not having brought their claims sooner. Nor do the pleadings rely on a change in legal advice. There is no unfairness to Nevsun as a result.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>d)</N><TI><UNDER>A Pleading of Postponement Does Not Automatically Leads to Waiver of Privilege Over the Pleaded Discovery Date</UNDER></TI>
<P>41. Not only does the application of the principles recently set out by this Court in <EM>Soprema</EM> and <EM>HMB</EM> require that the order below be set aside, the authorities the chambers judge relied on below do not support the proposition that a postponement claim necessarily leads to a waiver of privilege over the pleaded discovery date.</P>
<P>42. First, the authorities the chambers judge relied on below were decided prior to <EM>Soprema</EM> and <EM>HMB</EM>. To the extent that any of them suggest that waiver of privilege is established by the mere fact that a party puts its state of mind at issue, or because privileged communications might be relevant to an issue in dispute, they are inconsistent with this Court's recent jurisprudence and this reasoning should not be followed. The law is now clear that a finding of implicit waiver requires a party to have put legal advice or its understanding of the law in issue by relying on legal advice to justify or explain its conduct.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Soprema</EM> at para 53; <EM>HMB</EM> at paras 44&ndash;47.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>43. Secondly, the passage from Mr. de Vries' 2014 journal article, which the chambers judge placed considerable weight on, should not be taken as authoritative. In his article, Mr. de Vries, argues that the time period over which privilege is waived should include the pleaded discovery date.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Reasons at para 80, AR, Tab 16, at pp. 171-172; de Vries at 252.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Neither of the two Ontario Superior Court of Justice decisions Mr. de Vries relied on for this point, however, actually support this proposition. In <CASEREF><SOC>Davenport v. Roughley Estate</SOC></CASEREF>, the period of time over which Master Beaudoin found that privilege had been waived went up to, but did not include, the earliest possible pleaded triggering date for the start of the limitation period (although the applicant had not requested that it extend further).<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Davenport v. Roughley Estate</SOC><CITE>2003 CarswellOnt 766</CITE><COURTJUR>SC</COURTJUR></CASEREF> at paras 2 and 9.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> In <CASEREF><SOC>Lawless v. Anderson</SOC></CASEREF>, it is unclear from Master Hawkins short endorsement whether the period of waiver deriving from the postponement pleading included the pleaded discovery date of June 6, 2005.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Lawless v. Anderson</SOC><CITE>2009 CanLII 58602</CITE><COURTJUR>SC</COURTJUR></CASEREF> (&ldquo;<EM>Lawless</EM>&rdquo;) at paras 7-8.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Master Hawkins' conclusion was that the waiver of privilege on this basis extended &ldquo;until June 2005&rdquo;.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Lawless</EM> at para 8.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>44. Not only is Mr. de Vries' argument not supported by this case law, his comments appear directed at situations where the plaintiff was represented before the pleaded discovery date, as he argues that &ldquo;[w]hen a plaintiff has access to a lawyer prior to the alleged discovery of a claim, the lawyer's possible role in the discovery of that claim cannot be ignored.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>de Vries at 230.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> This plainly distinguishes the circumstances here, where the plaintiffs plead that that they did not have access to a Canadian lawyer prior to the earliest possible discovery date. Since the plaintiffs do not rely on a change in legal advice or in their legal counsel's knowledge, there can be no concern that preventing Nevsun from accessing privileged communications arising out of the first meeting with counsel leads to any unfair advantage for the plaintiffs.</P>
<P>45. Third, neither of the British Columbia cases the chambers judge relied where the period of waiver included the pleaded discovery date stand for the proposition that a pleading of postponement necessarily leads to a waiver of privilege over the first alleged date of discovery of the claim. Neither case expressly considers the issue and both are clearly distinguishable from the circumstances here.</P>
<P>46. In <CASEREF><SOC>Harry v. British Columbia</SOC></CASEREF>, the plaintiffs' alleged that they did not receive <UNDER>&ldquo;appropriate legal advice</UNDER> or a sufficient measure of certainty as to the reasonable prospect of success&rdquo; (emphasis added) until roughly 29 years after the act giving rise to the claim occurred.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Harry v. British Columbia</SOC><CITE>2001 BCSC 1566</CITE><PARANUM>3, 10-11</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Yet, they had received legal advice about transactions similar to the subject matter of the litigation during that timespan. The plaintiffs in <EM>Harry</EM> had therefore expressly relied on the on the &ldquo;appropriateness&rdquo; of the legal advice they received on or after the earliest pled discovery date. This is not the case here, where the plaintiffs do not plead that their claims became discoverable once they received a certain quality of legal advice. Instead, they plead that they were unable to bring their claims until they had <UNDER>access</UNDER> to any type of legal advice from a Canadian lawyer at all.</P>
<P>47. Further, a key factor in <EM>Harry</EM> is that in response to the plaintiffs' plea that the <EM>Limitation Act</EM> did not apply, the defendants had raised the equitable defence of laches, meaning that the reasons for the plaintiffs' delay in bringing the action up to the date of filing was in issue. This point was emphasized by Justice Esson, when he concluded that &ldquo;in the particular circumstances of this case&rdquo;, including in particular the plea of laches, the chambers judge had not erred.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Harry v. British Columbia</SOC><CITE>2002 BCCA 557</CITE><PARANUM>15</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>48. In <EM>Camosun College</EM>, Justice Affleck rejected the defendants' argument that the plaintiff's plea that the limitation period was postponed meant that privilege over the file of the plaintiff's former lawyer was implicitly waived up to the date the notice of civil claim was filed.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Camosun College</EM> at para 36.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Instead, Justice Affleck agreed with the plaintiff that the waiver of the former lawyer's file on this basis did not extend beyond the date when the plaintiff received an engineering report that it accepted started the limitation period.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Camosun College</EM> at para 36.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> While the alleged discovery date was included in the period of waiver, this was the plaintiff's position. There is therefore no analysis in the case about whether the period of waiver from the postponement plea should include the pleaded discovery date.</P>
<P>49. There is no general proposition that a period of waiver flowing from a postponement claim necessarily extends up to, and includes, the alleged discovery date so that the defendant may fully explore the shift in the plaintiff's discovery of the claim. Such a rule would not align with the principles set out in <EM>HMB</EM> and <EM>Soprema</EM> as it is detached from the key question of whether the plaintiff has actually injected legal advice or its understanding of the law into the litigation through relying on legal advice to justify its conduct.</P>
<P>50. Further, such a proposition would lead to inconsistent results. In <EM>Camosun College</EM> for example, any privileged communications concerning the engineering report may or may not have occurred until days after counsel received the report. Here, what legal advice was communicated at the first meeting might vary significantly between the plaintiffs. For some, it could be that no substantive communications occurred until the second meeting. The arbitrary nature of such a result demonstrates that there is no special rule for waiver of privilege flowing from a postponement plea that grants defendants access to privileged communications occurring on the pleaded discovery date. Instead, the principled approach set out by this Court applies&mdash;waiver of privilege requires a party to have placed legal advice in issue by relying on that advice as justification for its conduct.</P>
<P>51. As the reply pleadings do not place the legal advice that may have been communicated at the plaintiffs' first meeting with Canadian counsel in issue, it follows that the chambers judge erred in declaring that the plaintiffs had waived privilege over their first meetings with Canadian counsel.</P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><N><EM>2)</EM></N><TI><EM>Alternatively, the Declaration of Waiver is Overly Broad</EM></TI>
<P>52. Even if this Court concludes that the reply pleadings result in an implicit waiver of privilege, the chambers judge nevertheless erred in granting an overly broad declaration not limited to the subject of postponement. By granting a declaration of waiver over all aspects of the plaintiffs' cases up to and including their first meetings with Canadian counsel, the order below extends the scope of the waiver beyond what is relevant to the issue of whether the plaintiffs knew or should have known earlier that a lawsuit against Nevsun would be an appropriate means to seek a remedy for their injuries. In doing so, the order under appeal does not &ldquo;give effect to the near absolute protection of solicitor-client privilege.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>HMB</EM> at para 48.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>53. It is well-established that solicitor-client privilege&mdash;a substantive rule of law&mdash;must only be interfered with to the extent absolutely necessary.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Goodis v. Ontario (Ministry of Correctional Services)</SOC><CITE>2006 SCC 31</CITE><PARANUM>14-15</PARANUM></CASEREF>; <EM>Soprema</EM> at para 50;</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Solicitor-client privilege is &ldquo;jealously guarded&rdquo; for good reason.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Pritchard v. Ontario (Human Rights Commission)</SOC><CITE>2004 SCC 31</CITE><PARANUM>17</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> As Justice Binnie cautioned in <CASEREF><SOC>Canada (Privacy Commissioner) v. Blood Tribe Department of Health</SOC></CASEREF>, &ldquo;[e]xperience shows that people who have a legal problem will often not make a clean breast of the facts to a lawyer without an assurance of confidentiality &ldquo;as close to absolute as possible&rdquo;.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Canada (Privacy Commissioner) v. Blood Tribe Department of Health</SOC><CITE>2008 SCC 44</CITE><PARANUM>9</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The privilege is fundamentally important to the legal system and plays a key role in facilitating access to justice.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Alberta Information and Privacy Commissioner v. University of Calgary</SOC><CITE>2016 SCC 53</CITE><PARANUM>34</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Here, since the order below is disconnected from the discovery process, any unwarranted intrusion into privileged communications has the potential to also compromise the fairness of the eventual trials on the merits.</P>
<P>54. Waiver over a discrete issue will not generally lead to waiver over every aspect of the litigation. In <CASEREF><SOC>Souter v. 375561 B.C. Ltd.</SOC></CASEREF>, Justice Goldie confirmed that where privilege over one topic has been implicitly waived, the waiver does not extend to all purposes relevant to the issues in dispute.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Souter v. 375561 B.C. Ltd.</SOC><CITE>1995 CanLII 83</CITE><COURTJUR>BCCA</COURTJUR></CASEREF> (&ldquo;<EM>Souter</EM>&rdquo;) at para 25.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Instead, the waiver in that case only extended to the subject of the waiver, which concerned whether the party's lawyer was responsible for a mistake in an affidavit.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Souter</EM> at paras 21, 24-25.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Similarly, in <CASEREF><SOC>McDonnell v. Langret Investments, S.A.</SOC></CASEREF>, Justice Cumming concluded that an appellant's affidavit evidence that his former counsel was to blame for his failure to attend a hearing led to a waiver of privilege over the communications referenced in the affidavit but did not extend any further.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>McDonnell v. Langret Investments</SOC><CITE>1998 CanLII 6486</CITE><COURTJUR>BCCA in Chambers</COURTJUR></CASEREF> at para 17.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> In other words, the waiver only extended to those privileged communications the appellant specifically relied on.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Brown v. Clark Wilson LLP</SOC><CITE>2014 BCCA 185</CITE><PARANUM>32</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>55. Limiting the scope of the waiver of privilege to the specific subject matter of the waiver is also consistent with Justice Harris's conclusion in <EM>Soprema</EM> that solicitor-client privilege must only yield in clearly defined and limited circumstances.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Soprema</EM> at para 51.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Waiver over one issue in the litigation (discoverability) should not lead to waiver over every other issue.</P>
<P>56. Here, if there was a waiver of privilege flowing from the reply pleadings, the subject matter of the waiver cannot be broader than communications relating to whether the claims were discoverable before the plaintiffs met Canadian counsel. Any other privileged communications between counsel and the plaintiffs are irrelevant to Nevsun's ability to test the plaintiffs' pleadings that the claims were not discoverable until they had access to Canadian counsel.</P>
<P>57. If the reply pleadings implicitly waive privilege, the waiver should be limited to communications regarding whether the plaintiffs knew or ought to have known prior to meeting Canadian counsel that an action against Nevsun in Canada would be appropriate. The disclosure of communications that are not relevant to this question cannot possibly be necessary to ensure fairness between the parties or meet the requirement that privileged communication only be disclosed where &ldquo;absolutely necessary&rdquo;.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Soprema</EM> at para 50.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><N><EM>3)</EM></N><TI><EM>The Reasons Fail to Consider Litigation Privilege</EM></TI>
<P>58. In addition to the chambers judge's errors concerning his declaration that the plaintiffs had waived solicitor-client privilege, he also erred in ordering the production of documents relating to the retainer of Ms. Chyrum.</P>
<BLOCK3><N>a)</N><TI><UNDER>The Details of Ms. Chyrum's Retainer are Protected by Litigation Privilege</UNDER></TI>
<P>59. In ordering the plaintiffs to produce &ldquo;documents relating to or containing the particulars of the retainer or engagement of Ms. Elsa Chyrum&rdquo;,<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Order para 4, AR, Tab 15, p. 149.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> the chambers judge erred in principle by not applying the principles of litigation privilege when considering whether the terms of the retainer ought to be produced.</P>
<P>60. The purpose of litigation privilege is to create a zone of privacy over a litigant's preparation of a case for trial. The privilege is &ldquo;based upon the need for a protected area to facilitate investigation and preparation of a case for trial by the adversarial advocate.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Blank v. Canada (Minister of Justice)</SOC><CITE>2006 SCC 39</CITE></CASEREF> (&ldquo;<EM>Blank</EM>&rdquo;), at para 28, citing R.J. Sharpe, &ldquo;Claiming Privilege in the Discovery Process&rdquo;, in <EM>Special Lectures of the Law Society of Upper Canada</EM> (1984), 163, at pp. 164-65.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> It provides &ldquo;a protected area in which communications and documents created for and used in the process of preparing for and engaging in litigation are free from &ldquo;adversarial interference&rdquo; and &ldquo;premature disclosure&rdquo;.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Raj v. Khosravi</SOC><CITE>2015 BCCA 49</CITE><PARANUM>7</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>61. Litigation privilege is a class privilege, meaning that communications created for the dominant purpose of litigation that is pending or reasonably apprehended are presumptively protected from disclosure.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Lizotte v. Aviva Insurance Company of Canada</SOC><CITE>2016 SCC 52</CITE></CASEREF> (&ldquo;<EM>Lizotte</EM>&rdquo;) at para 33.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> There is no obligation on the party asserting privilege to prove that the privilege should apply based on a case-by-case balancing of the competing interests at stake.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Lizotte</EM> at paras 37&ndash;39.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>62. The privilege covers communications between counsel and third parties, including non-confidential information received from third parties in the course of counsel's work preparing for trial.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Blank</EM> at paras 27 and 32.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Instructions or communications passed to third parties, such as potential experts or consultants, are protected by the privilege.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Sopinka</EM> at 14.223.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Although the Rules of Court provide for the limited lifting of privilege when an expert report is to be tendered as evidence,<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Supreme Court Civil Rules</EM>, R. 11-6(8) (b).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> the default is that litigation privilege applies to communications with third party for the dominant purpose of pending or apprehended litigation.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Blank</EM> at para 38.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>63. Retainer agreements with third party agents of litigation counsel clearly meet the test for the presumptive application of privilege. For example, in <CASEREF><SOC>Re Gault Estate</SOC></CASEREF>, the Alberta Court of Queen's Bench found that the terms one party's engagement of an accountant for the purpose of considering potential litigation was litigation privileged.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Gault Estate (Re)</SOC><CITE>2016 ABQB 53</CITE><PARANUM>31</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The Alberta Court of Appeal upheld this finding, reasoning that &ldquo;any communications with the accountant with a view to obtaining his professional assistance&rdquo; in contemplation of the litigation were privileged so long as the dominant purpose of the communications was to prepare for litigation.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Gault Estate v. Gault Estate</SOC><CITE>2016 ABCA 208</CITE><PARANUM>14</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Similarly, in <CASEREF><SOC>Marchese v. Knowles</SOC></CASEREF>, the Ontario Superior Court found that letters of engagement sent to a surveillance firm retained to conduct surveillance of an opposing party were protected by litigation privilege.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Marchese v. Knowles</SOC><CITE>2009 CanLII 12116</CITE><COURTJUR>ONSC</COURTJUR></CASEREF> at para 30.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>64. Here, the chambers judge ordered the plaintiffs to disclose the particulars of their counsel's retainer of a third party for the purposes of the litigation. These communications are clearly covered by litigation privilege.</P>
<P>65. Yet, the extent of the chambers judge's consideration of litigation privilege is a passing reference to its well-established nature and importance.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Reasons at para 71, AR, Tab 16, p. 170.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> There is no analysis or consideration of litigation privilege and whether it might apply to communications involving Ms. Chyrum or to the terms of her engagement by legal counsel.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Reasons at paras 83-84, 101&ndash;111, AR, Tab 16, pp. 176-177.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Instead, the reasons focus on the principles that apply when determining when communications with a third party are covered by solicitor-client privilege.</P>
<P>66. The lack of consideration of litigation privilege is demonstrated by the chambers judge's discussion of &ldquo;third party privilege&rdquo;. That discussion ignores the role that litigation privilege, in addition to solicitor-client privilege, plays in protecting communications between parties and third parties from disclosure. Notably, in <CASEREF><SOC>Bank of Montreal v. Toratora</SOC></CASEREF>,<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Bank of Montreal v. Tortora</SOC><CITE>2010 BCSC 1430</CITE></CASEREF> (&ldquo;<EM>Tortora</EM>&rdquo;).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> the case which the chambers judge relied on for articulation of the general principles regarding third party privilege, a claim of litigation privilege over the same documents had previously failed and was not at issue.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Tortora</EM> at paras 5&ndash;7; <CASEREF><SOC>Bank of Montreal v. Tortora</SOC><CITE>2009 BCSC 1224</CITE><PARANUM>32</PARANUM></CASEREF>; see also <CASEREF><SOC>Bank of Montreal v. Tortora</SOC><CITE>2009 BCSC 1512</CITE><PARANUM>9</PARANUM></CASEREF>, where Mr. Justice Butler (as he then was) found that the plaintiff still had an opportunity to assert solicitor-client privilege over some of the documents, despite the claim of litigation privilege having failed.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> There was therefore no question in that case about whether the communications were privileged on any basis other than solicitor-client privilege.</P>
<P>67. This is not a case where the plaintiffs failed to claim privilege when they should have done so. Rather, the plaintiffs were not given an opportunity to establish privilege over the terms of Ms. Chyrum's retainer, since Nevsun had not requested this relief in its notice of application or applied for it at the hearing. This fundamental unfairness deprived the plaintiffs of an opportunity to establish litigation privilege over the terms of their counsel's retainer of a third party engaged for the purposes of the litigation. For these reasons, this order must be overturned.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>b)</N><TI><UNDER>Ms. Chyrum's Retainer Does Not Assist in Determining Which Communications Are Litigation Privileged</UNDER></TI>
<P>68. Further, the chambers judge's failure to consider and apply the principles of litigation privilege also led to his erroneous conclusion that the particulars of Ms. Chyrum's retainer would be helpful to determining which of the plaintiffs' communications with Ms. Chyrum ought to be produced.</P>
<P>69. In ordering production of the retainer on the basis that it &ldquo;may well assist in delineating Ms. Chyrum's precise role while acting as a third party agent for counsel&rdquo;,<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Reasons at para 109, AR, Tab 16, p. 177.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> the chambers judge failed to consider that litigation privilege may also apply to these communications and make this inquiry unnecessary. While solicitor-client privilege only extends to communications involving third parties when the function of the third party is essential to the solicitor-client relationship,<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Tortora</EM> at para 18.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> litigation privilege does not include this limitation. It applies to plaintiff-third party communications so long as the dominant purpose of the communications was to prepare for litigation.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Gichuru v. British Columbia (Information and Privacy Commissioner)</SOC><CITE>2014 BCCA 259</CITE><PARANUM>31</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> There is no requirement that the third party plays an &ldquo;essential&rdquo; function in the lawyer-client relationship.</P>
<P>70. So long as the communications between Ms. Chyrum and the plaintiffs are for the dominant purpose of the litigation, it is unnecessary to examine the particulars of Ms. Chyrum's role any further. The plaintiffs' evidence is that their counsel is producing communications between Ms. Chyrum and the plaintiffs where the dominant purpose was not in furtherance of the litigation.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Hill #9 at paras 3, 5, 10, AB, Tab 2.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> If it wishes, Nevsun can challenge the plaintiffs' privilege list through the ordinary procedure of challenging the designation of particular documents. There is no need for Nevsun to explore the exact nature of Ms. Chyrum's engagement generally.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>c)</N><TI><UNDER>The Allegations of Bias Are Irrelevant in the Context of this Application</UNDER></TI>
<P>71. Finally, the chambers judge's finding that disclosure of the particulars of Ms. Chyrum's retainer may be &ldquo;material to any potential allegations of bias arising from her translator and interpreter functions&rdquo; is not grounded in the context of this application. None of Ms. Chyrum's translations were at issue below. Nor did Nevsun seek to have the Court revisit its 2016 decision that certain affidavits translated by Ms. Chyrum were admissible.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Araya 2016</EM> at paras 216-217.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> If Nevsun wishes to challenge the objectivity of an affidavit translated by Ms. Chyrum, it should do so in the context of a particular affidavit, not as vague and generalized assertions of impropriety not tied to any particular piece of evidence.</P>
<P>72. Even accepting Nevsun's generalized approach, it is difficult to see how the information that Ms. Chyrum acts as an agent to communicate to clients calls into question the objectivity of her translations. In <CASEREF><SOC>Luu v. Wang</SOC></CASEREF>, the objectivity of the translation was questioned because the interpreter was the wife or ex-wife of the defendant and the daughter of the affiant.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Luu v. Wang</SOC><CITE>2011 BCSC 1201</CITE><PARANUM>2-3</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The focus is on whether a relationships between the party and the translator suggests a lack of objectivity. An employment or agency relationship between counsel and the interpreter is wholly different.</P>
<P>73. These vague assertions of bias should not entitle Nevsun to trench into the plaintiffs' protected zone of litigation privilege. Nevsun's speculation that Ms. Chyrum's translations may lack impartiality is no less speculative than it was in 2016.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Araya 2016</EM> at para 216.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>74. Overall, the chambers judge's reasons indicate that he erred by failing to consider or apply the principles of litigation privilege. Because Nevsun did not request the particulars of Ms. Chyrum's retainer in its notice of application, the plaintiffs were denied the opportunity to establish that these communications are privileged, which they clearly are. In any event, the particulars of Ms. Chyrum's retainer are unnecessary to determine the issues raised in the underlying application. The third ground of appeal should be allowed.</P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="VI">PART 4&mdash;NATURE OF ORDER SOUGHT</TI>
<P>75. The plaintiffs seek an order allowing the appeal and setting aside paragraphs 2&ndash;4 of the order below. Alternatively, if the Court decides that the declaration that the plaintiffs have waived privilege up to and including the date upon which each plaintiff first met Canadian counsel should stand, the plaintiffs submit that the declaration should be limited to documents and communications relating to whether the plaintiffs knew or ought to have known prior to meeting Canadian counsel that an action against Nevsun in Canada would be appropriate.</P>
