<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="II">OPENING STATEMENT</TI>
<P>The plaintiffs, a group that now includes approximately 80 Eritrean refugees, have sued Nevsun Resources Ltd. (&ldquo;Nevsun&rdquo;) alleging that Nevsun was party to various wrongs committed by arms of the Eritrean government at the Bisha mine between 2006 and 2014. Ten actions have been commenced over the last four years. Among other things, Nevsun pleads that the plaintiffs' claims are time-barred under Eritrean law and, alternatively, under the <EM>Limitation Act</EM> (2012) or the <EM>Limitation Act</EM> (1996). In response to Nevsun's limitations defence, the plaintiffs have pleaded that the limitation period is postponed because they did not have the requisite understanding of their legal rights against Nevsun in Canada and only could have brought their claim after they had met with Canadian counsel to &ldquo;ascertain and assess&rdquo; those rights against Nevsun.</P>
<P>In the court below, the plaintiffs agreed that the plea of postponement waived privilege, but maintained that the waiver did not extend to their first meeting with counsel. The case management judge correctly found that the postponement plea waived privilege over documents and communications exchanged during the plaintiffs' first meeting with counsel. The plaintiffs' replies expressly and voluntarily assert reliance on advice from a counsel at a specific meeting as the event that led to discovery of a claim against Nevsun. Fairness demands that Nevsun be permitted to test this pleading to determine whether information about a potential claim against Nevsun was available to the plaintiffs at an earlier date. The case management judge made no error in his ruling about the scope of the waiver.</P>
<P>Ms. Chyrum has acted in several capacities in her dealings with the plaintiffs. She was reportedly retained by Canadian counsel months before any plaintiffs met counsel and before litigation could have been contemplated. The case management judge correctly ordered disclosure of her retainer agreement with Canadian counsel in order to assess the plaintiffs' claim to privilege.</P></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="III">PART 1&mdash;STATEMENT OF FACTS</TI>
<BLOCK2><N>A.</N><TI><UNDER>Background to the Actions</UNDER></TI>
<P>1. The plaintiffs claim that the Bisha mine was built using forced labour and that Nevsun is liable as an accessory to wrongs committed by various arms of the Eritrean government. The plaintiffs allege that these wrongs occurred between 2006 and 2014. Nevsun denies these allegations.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Appeal Record (&ldquo;AR&rdquo;), Tab 16, Reasons for Judgment of Justice Abrioux (&ldquo;Reasons&rdquo;), paras. 2&ndash;12.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>2. The proceeding now comprises ten separate actions including more than 80 plaintiffs. Justice Abrioux was the case management judge for all actions before his elevation to this Court. The first action, <CASEREF><SOC>Araya v. Nevsun Resources Ltd.</SOC></CASEREF>, was commenced on November 20, 2014 (the &ldquo;Araya Action&rdquo;). After Justice Abrioux ordered that the Araya Action could not proceed as a representative action, nine additional actions were commenced between October 19, 2016 and May 14, 2018 (the &ldquo;Related Actions&rdquo;, and with the Araya Action, the &ldquo;Actions&rdquo;).<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>AR, Tab 16, Reasons, para. 2.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>3. The Actions currently stand at a &ldquo;critical juncture&rdquo;.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Araya v. Nevsun Resources Ltd.</SOC><CITE>2019 BCSC 262</CITE><PARANUM>10, 20-21</PARANUM></CASEREF> (&ldquo;Document Reasons&rdquo;).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The plaintiffs intend to apply to proceed by way of a series of test cases (the &ldquo;bellwether&rdquo; trials) later in 2019. The trial in one action, Araya, has been set as a placeholder and is presently scheduled to begin in April 2020.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><N>B.</N><TI><UNDER>The pleadings</UNDER></TI>
<P>4. In its responses to the various notices of civil claim, Nevsun pleads that the actions are statute-barred. Nevsun first pleads that Eritrean law governs these proceedings. Eritrean law imposes a limitation period and has no discoverability rules. In the alternative, Nevsun relies on British Columbia limitations legislation. The plaintiffs incorrectly state that Nevsun has relied only on the current <EM>Limitation Act</EM>, S.B.C. 2012, c. 13 (the &ldquo;<EM>New Act</EM>&rdquo;).<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Appellants' Factum, para. 4.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> In fact, Nevsun's responses rely on the <EM>New Act</EM> as well as the <EM>Limitation Act</EM>, R.S.B.C. 1996, c. 266 (the &ldquo;<EM>Old Act</EM>&rdquo;).<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>AR, Tab 2, Response to Civil Claim filed February 13, 2015, paras. 11-12.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>5. The plaintiffs have filed replies in each of the Actions (the &ldquo;Replies&rdquo;) responding to Nevsun's limitation defences. The case management judge observed that the Replies have evolved through the course of the litigation, but are substantially similar.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>AR, Tab 16, Reasons, para. 64.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The plaintiffs plead that there is no applicable limitation period. In the alternative, the plaintiffs say that the applicable limitation period has been postponed or tolled or both.</P>
<P>6. The plaintiffs filed the first Reply in January 2017 in the Araya Action. This pleading is different from Replies in the Related Actions. The Araya Reply pleads postponement to the date the Araya notice of civil claim was filed (November 2014).<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>AR, Tab 3, Araya Reply filed January 31, 2017, para. 1; Tab 16, Reasons, para. 65.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> During argument in the court below, plaintiffs' counsel advised he would be bringing an application to amend the Araya Reply. The waiver application in the Araya Action was adjourned to permit the plaintiffs to bring an application to amend.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>AR, Tab 16, Reasons, paras. 65-66, 91&ndash;95. The plaintiffs have since amended the Araya Reply to follow substantially the words used in the Common Plea. Respondent's Appeal Book, Tab 1, Amended Araya Reply filed April 25, 2019.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>7. Replies in the Related Actions were filed between February 9, 2018 and September 7, 2018.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>AR, Tabs 4&ndash;12, Replies.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The Reply in the Mekonen Action is representative of the common plea of postponement (the &ldquo;Common Plea&rdquo;)<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>AR, Tab 16, Reasons, para. 67.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE>:
<QUOTE><P>1. In reply to paragraphs 6 and 7 of Part 3 of the defendant's Response to Civil Claim, this action is not subject to any limitation period. In the alternative, any limitation period applicable to each of the plaintiffs' claims was:
<P1>(a) postponed until at least the time when they <UNDER>accessed the legal advice of Canadian counsel necessary to ascertain and assess their legal rights in Canada as against the defendant</UNDER>; and</P1></P>
<P>&ellipsis;</P>
<P>8. In the alternative, any limitation period applicable to each plaintiff's claims in this action was postponed until at least the time when they <UNDER>accessed the legal advice of Canadian counsel necessary to ascertain and assess their legal rights in Canada as against Nevsun.</UNDER></P>
<P>9. <UNDER>The plaintiffs' claims against Nevsun involve complex and novel issues of domestic tort law and customary international law.</UNDER></P>
<P>&ellipsis;</P>
<P>11. <UNDER>Prior to accessing the legal advice of Canadian counsel necessary to ascertain and assess their legal rights in Canada as against Nevsun,</UNDER> the plaintiffs lacked the means to discover that they <UNDER>may have a claim against it</UNDER> and that <UNDER>a court action in the courts of British Columbia was the appropriate means of seeking a remedy against Nevsun.</UNDER></P>
<P>12. Particulars of the plaintiffs' circumstances relevant to postponement of any applicable limitation period include:
<P1>&ellipsis;</P1>
<P1>(c) in order to <UNDER>ascertain and assess their rights against the defendant Nevsun, the plaintiffs required the benefit of legal advice from Canadian lawyers</UNDER>.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>AR, Tab 11, Mekonen Reply.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P1></P>
<P>[Underlining added.]</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>8. The Replies in the Related Actions provide details of each plaintiff's circumstances and the date on which each plaintiff first met with &ldquo;Canadian counsel&rdquo;. These dates, which range between December 2013 and February 2018, are alleged to be the dates when the plaintiffs discovered a potential claim against Nevsun.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>See e.g., AR, Tab 11, Mekonen Reply, para. 14(b).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><N>C.</N><TI><UNDER>Examinations for discovery</UNDER></TI>
<P>9. Examinations for discovery of certain plaintiffs took place in the fall of 2018. During these examinations, plaintiffs' counsel objected to any questions concerning the first meeting with counsel on the on the basis of solicitor-client privilege.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>See e.g. AAB, Tab 3, Dhanpaul #9, Ex. &ldquo;A&rdquo;, Q763.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>10. Plaintiffs' counsel also objected to certain questions regarding communications with Elsa Chyrum on the basis of litigation and solicitor-client privilege.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>See e.g. AAB, Tab 3, Dhanpaul #9, Ex. &ldquo;A&rdquo;, Q760&ndash;765.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> At the hearing below, and for the first time, the plaintiffs maintained that Ms. Chyrum is an agent of counsel who had been retained since May 1, 2013 to &ldquo;communicate with witnesses, potential clients and clients&rdquo; in the actions against Nevsun.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>AR, Tab 16, Reasons, para. 105; AAB, Tab 4, Affidavit of A.D. Lascaris, made December 21, 2018 (&ldquo;Lascaris Affidavit&rdquo;), para. 3.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The judge found that Ms. Chyrum in fact wore &ldquo;many hats&rdquo;, including human rights activist and agent of counsel.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>AR, Tab 16, Reasons, paras. 101&ndash;105; AAB, Tab 1, Affidavit #8 of Roxanne Dhanpaul, filed December 19, 2018 (&ldquo;Dhanpaul #8&rdquo;), Ex. A&ndash;H.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Ms. Chyrum has also assisted plaintiffs with asylum claims.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>AAB, Tab 2, Affidavit #9 of Kimberly Hill, filed December 24, 2018 (&ldquo;Hill 2&rdquo;), Ex. A.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>11. Ms. Chyrum also translated affidavits that were filed in court. In previous interlocutory proceedings, Nevsun objected to these translations, raising concerns about Ms. Chyrum's independence and impartiality.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>AAB, Tab 1, Dhanpaul #8, para. 5; <CASEREF><SOC>Araya v. Nevsun Resources Ltd.</SOC><CITE>2016 BCSC 1856</CITE><PARANUM>212&ndash;217</PARANUM></CASEREF> (&ldquo;<EM>Araya 2016</EM>&rdquo;).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> At the time of these objections, the plaintiffs did not disclose that Ms. Chyrum was their agent and did not disclose details of her agreement to act as an agent.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>AR, Tab 16, Reasons, para. 105.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><N>D.</N><TI><UNDER>Nevsun's application</UNDER></TI>
<P>12. In December 2018, Nevsun brought an application seeking an order that the plaintiffs had waived privilege over documents and communications arising from the Common Plea and an order requiring the plaintiffs to produce documents. Nevsun also sought an order declaring that no privilege attached to documents and communications with Ms. Chyrum, or, alternatively, that any privilege had been waived. Nevsun sought rulings on objections made in discovery flowing from these orders.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>AR, Tab 13, Notice of Application (&ldquo;NOA&rdquo;), Part 1, paras. 1&ndash;3, 4, 6; Part 2, 10&ndash;13.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>13. Nevsun's motion did not seek production of specific documents because the plaintiffs did not provide lists of documents that properly listed privileged documents. Only recently have the plaintiffs agreed to provide lists of documents that comply with the rules for listing privileged documents.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>AR, Tab 13, NOA, Part 2, para. 11. The plaintiffs have since agreed to provide a compliant part 4 list of documents: Document Reasons, para. 33.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><N>E.</N><TI><UNDER>Reasons of case management judge</UNDER></TI>
<P>14. The case management judge confirmed that the parties &ldquo;essentially agree on the legal framework&rdquo; governing solicitor-client and litigation privilege and waiver. He correctly instructed himself that &ldquo;[t]he law has clearly recognized the importance and value of both forms of privilege, and the virtually sacrosanct status of the former.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>AR, Tab 16, Reasons, paras. 69&ndash;71.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>15. There was no dispute that the plaintiffs had waived privilege: &ldquo;[t]he plaintiffs admit that, as a result of the plea of postponement, their state of mind is in issue and privilege has been waived&rdquo;. The remaining issue was the &ldquo;scope of the waiver&rdquo; and &ldquo;the facts and documents that must be disclosed&rdquo;. The plaintiffs argued that waiver did not include their first meeting with counsel because the Replies only pointed to &ldquo;access&rdquo; to Canadian legal advice. According to the plaintiffs, &ldquo;the waiver of privilege ends at the time the &lsquo;access&rsquo; commenced, which is when the meeting commenced&rdquo;.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>AR, Tab 16, Reasons, paras. 70, 85&ndash;88.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>16. The case management judge rejected this argument. The judge emphasized the language of the Common Plea, as exemplified by the Reply in the Mekonen Action, which stated that the plaintiffs &ldquo;<EM>required</EM>&rdquo; legal advice from Canadian counsel to &ldquo;assess and ascertain&rdquo; their legal rights as against Nevsun in Canada.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>AR, Tab 16, Reasons, paras. 89-90.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The case management judge reasoned that it could only be as a result of the first meeting with counsel that the plaintiffs' state of mind would have transitioned from lack of knowledge or certainty to a knowledge of &ldquo;a reasonable likelihood of success against Nevsun in a Canadian court&rdquo;. The judge ruled that by reason of the Common Plea, each of the plaintiffs had waived privilege over communications and documents relating to the pursuit of the Actions up to and including the date upon which they first met Canadian counsel.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>AR, Tab 16, Reasons, paras. 90, 112, Tab 15, Order, para. 2.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>17. With respect to Ms. Chyrum, the plaintiffs agreed that communications between Ms. Chyrum and plaintiffs while she was wearing her &ldquo;activist hat&rdquo; were not privileged.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>AR, Tab 16, Reasons, para. 106.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The case management judge found that &ldquo;the real issue is when Ms. Chyrum was acting as an assistant or agent to legal counsel, since those communications would raise the issue of third party privilege.&rdquo; Because Ms. Chyrum exercised a dual role, the case management judge ordered that her retainer be disclosed as &ldquo;[i]t may well assist in delineating Ms. Chyrum's precise role while acting as a third party agent for counsel and/or be material to any potential allegations of bias arising from her translator and interpreter functions.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>AR, Tab 16, Reasons, paras. 107&ndash;109, 112.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></BLOCK2></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="IV">PART 2&mdash;ISSUES ON APPEAL</TI>
<P>18. In response to the errors asserted by the plaintiffs, Nevsun submits:
<P1>A. The case management judge did not err in concluding that the admitted waiver of privilege included the plaintiffs' first meeting with Canadian counsel.</P1>
<P1>B. The case management judge did not err by making an overly broad order regarding the scope of the waiver.</P1>
<P1>C. The case management judge did not err in ordering disclosure of Ms. Chyrum's retainer.</P1></P></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="V">PART 3&mdash;ARGUMENT</TI>
<BLOCK2><N>A.</N><TI><UNDER>Overview</UNDER></TI>
<P>19. The parties agreed on the applicable law and the plaintiffs admitted that privilege had been waived. The narrow issue before the case management judge was whether the waiver included the plaintiffs' first meetings with counsel. The plaintiffs' pleadings explicitly rely on legal advice conveyed at those first meetings. Nevsun cannot test the claim of postponement without knowing what was communicated to the plaintiffs at those meetings. Fairness requires that Nevsun be permitted to investigate whether the information provided at those first meetings was or could have been available to the plaintiffs at an earlier date. The case management judge made no error in ruling that the plaintiffs' waiver of privilege included the first meetings with counsel.</P>
<P>20. Similarly, in light of the fact that Ms. Chyrum has acted in different roles in her dealings with the plaintiffs, disclosure of her retainer is required to assess the plaintiffs' claim that communications with her are protected by litigation privilege. The case management judge correctly ruled that her retainer should be disclosed.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><N>B.</N><TI><UNDER>Standard of review</UNDER></TI>
<P>21. This Court has said that whether a judge correctly identified and applied the test governing waiver of privilege is a question of law.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Soprema Inc. v. Wolrige Mahon LLP</SOC><CITE>2016 BCCA 471</CITE><PARANUM>16</PARANUM></CASEREF> (&ldquo;<EM>Soprema</EM>&rdquo;); <CASEREF><SOC>H.M.B. Holdings Limited v. Replay Resorts Inc.</SOC><CITE>2018 BCCA 263</CITE><PARANUM>29</PARANUM></CASEREF> (&ldquo;<EM>HMB</EM>&rdquo;).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Here, there was no dispute in the court below about the principles of law governing waiver of privilege arising out of a plea of postponement. The plaintiffs admitted there was a waiver of privilege. The only issue was the <EM>extent</EM> of that waiver. No question of law arises.</P>
<P>22. Other decisions of this Court state that whether privilege is waived is a question of mixed fact and law, reviewable on a standard of palpable and overriding error, unless an extricable question of law is identified.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Mayer v. Mayer</SOC><CITE>2012 BCCA 77</CITE><PARANUM>188</PARANUM></CASEREF>; <CASEREF><SOC>Do Process LP v. Infokey Software Inc.</SOC><CITE>2015 BCCA 52</CITE><PARANUM>16&ndash;20</PARANUM></CASEREF> (&ldquo;<EM>Do Process</EM>&rdquo;).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The case management judge made no extricable error of law. The scope of the admitted waiver of privilege was based on the case management judge's assessment of the pleadings in light of his knowledge of the history of the litigation.</P>
<P>23. The plaintiffs' appeal from the order to disclose Ms. Chyrum's retainer similarly raises no extricable question of law. The order turned on the judge's assessment of evidence and his determination of the proper scope of disclosure in the course of ongoing case management.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Shooting Star Amusements Ltd. v. Prince George Agricultural and Historical Association</SOC><CITE>2009 BCCA 452</CITE><PARANUM>8</PARANUM><DECIDER>Newbury J.A.</DECIDER><COURTJUR>in Chambers</COURTJUR></CASEREF> (&ldquo;<EM>Shooting Star</EM>&rdquo;).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>24. Even if this Court decides that this appeal raises questions of law, the case management judge's decisions were correct and should not be disturbed.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><N>C.</N><TI><UNDER>The Plaintiffs' Common Plea relies on legal advice and waives privilege</UNDER></TI>
<P>25. The Common Plea explicitly relies on legal advice as the essential element of the claimed postponement.</P>
<P>26. The Common Plea relies on two elements to achieve postponement of the limitation period. First, the Common Plea asserts that the plaintiffs did not and could not obtain legal advice on their rights against Nevsun. They were in a position of ignorance about their legal rights, which stopped them from bringing a claim at an earlier time.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>AR, Tab 11, Mekonen Reply, para. 11. See <CASEREF><SOC>07822484 B.C. Ltd. v. E-Pro Enterprises Inc.</SOC><CITE>2017 BCSC 2245</CITE><PARANUM>44</PARANUM></CASEREF> (&ldquo;<EM>E-Pro</EM>&rdquo;).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Second, the Common Plea asserts that the plaintiffs obtained legal advice during a particular meeting with Canadian counsel, at which time they &ldquo;ascertained and assessed&rdquo; their legal rights to bring a claim against Nevsun.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>AR, Tab 11, Mekonen Reply, para. 14(b).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The plaintiffs made a deliberate and voluntary election to identify the receipt of legal advice as the event that led to discovery of their claims.</P>
<P>27. The operative words here are &ldquo;ascertain and assess&rdquo;. The word &ldquo;assess&rdquo; means to &ldquo;judge or evaluate&rdquo;; the word &ldquo;ascertain&rdquo; means &ldquo;to find out as a definitive fact&rdquo; and &ldquo;achieve certainty&rdquo;.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Canadian Oxford Dictionary</EM>, 2d ed., Oxford University Press: 2004, <EM>sub verbo</EM> &ldquo;assess&rdquo;; <CASEREF><SOC>Schmidt v. Canada (Attorney General)</SOC><CITE>2016 FC 269</CITE><PARANUM>131</PARANUM><CASEHIST><CASEDISP>affirmed</CASEDISP><CASEREF><CITE>2018 FCA 55</CITE><PARANUM>49</PARANUM></CASEREF></CASEHIST></CASEREF>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The combined effect of these word choices is to confirm the plaintiffs' consideration of information leading to a conclusion or a result (an awareness of a claim, which starts the limitation period).</P>
<P>28. The plaintiffs' position that their postponement plea does not import reliance on legal advice, because they rely only on &ldquo;access&rdquo; to Canadian lawyers as the &ldquo;pleaded precursor&rdquo; to postponement, ignores the plain language of the Common Plea. The Common Plea does not only speak of &ldquo;access&rdquo; to a Canadian lawyer who might be available to represent them. Instead, the Common Plea specifically invokes the &ldquo;legal advice of Canadian counsel <UNDER>necessary</UNDER> to ascertain and assess their legal rights in Canada as against the defendant&rdquo;. The Common Plea makes the legal advice received in the first meeting a condition of the knowledge required for discoverability: the plea is that &ldquo;<UNDER>[p]rior to</UNDER> assessing legal advice of Canadian counsel necessary to ascertain and assess their legal rights&rdquo; no claim could be brought. Further, without this advice the plaintiffs could not know a Canadian court action was &ldquo;the appropriate means to obtain a remedy against Nevsun.&rdquo; Legal advice is an essential element of the postponement claim.</P>
<P>29. The plaintiffs voluntarily elected to rely on the legal advice provided during the first meeting with Canadian counsel. They did not have to do this. It was open to plead, for example, that their claims were postponed due to challenging personal circumstances. Instead, they pointed to legal advice received in their first meeting as the triggering event to answer a limitation defence.</P>
<P>30. For this reason, the plaintiffs incorrectly object that the case management judge made a &ldquo;speculative leap&rdquo; that communications at the first meeting were relevant to assessing the plaintiffs' pleas of postponement.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Appellants' Factum, paras. 31-32.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> No &ldquo;speculative leap&rdquo; or assumption is required. The relevance of those communications is evident on the plaintiffs' own pleadings. The actual substance of the advice need not be set out in the pleading.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Adam Dodek, <EM>Solicitor-Client Privilege</EM> (Toronto: Lexis Nexis, 2014) at 7.111.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>31. The fact that the plaintiffs have admitted that the limitations clock starts running from the time of the first meeting does not permit them to control the scope of their waiver of privilege. This Court has rejected the plaintiffs' underlying theory in this appeal that anything that occurred during the running of the limitation period is irrelevant to the question of discoverability.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Harry v. British Columbia</SOC><CITE>2002 BCCA 557</CITE><PARANUM>12&ndash;15</PARANUM></CASEREF> (&ldquo;<EM>Harry BCCA</EM>&rdquo;).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>32. On any analysis, the Common Plea amounts to a voluntary reliance on legal advice, obtained at the first meeting with counsel, as a material element of the plea of postponement.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><N>D.</N><TI><UNDER>There is no dispute on the law that a postponement plea waives privilege</UNDER></TI>
<P>33. The case management judge was cognizant of the sacrosanct nature of solicitor-client privilege.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>AR Tab 16, Reasons, para. 71.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> It was not in dispute, however, that a plea of postponement results in waiver of privilege because it puts at issue a party's state of mind. The plaintiffs admitted that &ldquo;as a result of the plea of postponement, their state of mind is in issue and privilege has been waived&rdquo;.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>AR Tab 16, Reasons, para. 70.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>34. The case management judge correctly relied on the two leading cases dealing with postponement and waiver: <CASEREF><SOC>Harry v. British Columbia</SOC></CASEREF><FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Harry v. British Columbia</SOC><CITE>2001 BCSC 1566</CITE></CASEREF> (&ldquo;<EM>Harry BCSC</EM>&rdquo;), affirmed, <EM>Harry BCCA</EM>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> and <CASEREF><SOC>Camosun College v. Levelton Engineering Ltd.</SOC></CASEREF><FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Camosun College v. Levelton Engineering Ltd.</SOC><CITE>2014 BCSC 1190</CITE></CASEREF> (&ldquo;<EM>Camosun</EM>&rdquo;).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>35. In <EM>Harry</EM>, Justice Vickers held that the plaintiffs had waived privilege over information and legal advice received up to the date they initiated proceedings. In that case, the plaintiff band commenced action against British Columbia and Canada in 1994. The defendants raised limitation defences and laches. The plaintiffs pleaded that they did not discover the claims until February 1993 when they received information from Canada and obtained legal advice. Justice Vickers held that the plea of postponement entitled the defendants to examine privileged communications:
<QUOTE><P>[19] The plaintiffs plead they couldn't have commenced proceedings at an earlier date because they lacked sufficient information. They say that information came to them sometime after February 1993. Those pleas constitute a waiver of privilege. <UNDER>The defendants are entitled to inquire into the knowledge acquired by the plaintiffs to test whether it might reasonably have been available at some earlier date or whether indeed it was information already in their possession from an earlier date</UNDER>. [Underlining added.]</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>36. On appeal, the plaintiffs agreed privilege was waived before February 1993, but refused to disclose information including and after that date. This Court upheld the judgment of Justice Vickers.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Harry BCCA</EM>, paras. 7, 15.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>37. <EM>Camosun</EM> follows <EM>Harry</EM> and confirms that a plea of postponement puts at issue a plaintiffs legal knowledge because to successfully claim postponement, &ldquo;it must be established that the party lacked the factual and legal knowledge necessary to start the action prior to the date in which it was actually commenced&rdquo;.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Camosun</EM>, para. 13.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> In that case, the Court agreed there had been a waiver of privilege up to and including the alleged day of discovery of the claim, which had been based on receipt of an expert report.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Camosun</EM>, paras. 36, 39.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>38. The article by Mr. de Vries, referenced by the case management judge, is consistent with the British Columbia judgments on postponement and waiver. Mr. de Vries correctly observes that the plaintiff has the exclusive power to identify the terms of the purported discovery date and the period of postponement. Given this power, the date of discovery selected by the plaintiff, whether by pleading or other representation, should be included in the waiver so that the defendant may test the assertion that the claim was not otherwise discoverable.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Jonathan de Vries, &ldquo;Privilege and Limitations: The Impact of Raising the Discoverability of Claims on Solicitor-Client Privilege&rdquo;, (2014) 43 Advocates Quarterly 219&ndash;256 at 251&ndash;253 (&ldquo;de Vries&rdquo;).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> This is the same point made by Justice Vickers in <EM>Harry</EM> and endorsed by this Court: the defendant should be allowed to test whether the plaintiff could have discovered the claim at an earlier time.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Harry BCSC</EM>, para. 19. See also <EM>E-Pro</EM>, para. 49.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>39. In this case, as the case management judge found, it could only be as a result of information conveyed at the first meeting with counsel that the plaintiffs' &ldquo;state of mind would have transitioned&rdquo; to the knowledge of a reasonable likelihood of success in a Canadian court&rdquo;.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>de Vries at 252; <EM>Harry BCSC</EM>, para. 15; Dodek at 7.112.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Waiver of privilege must include the first meeting with counsel.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><N>E.</N><TI><UNDER>Legal advice material to the postponement plea under B.C. limitations legislation</UNDER></TI>
<P>40. Even if the plaintiffs had not expressly pleaded reliance on legal advice, the receipt of legal advice would be relevant to a plea of postponement under B.C. limitations legislation.</P>
<P>41. Under the <EM>Old Act</EM>, the receipt of &ldquo;appropriate advice&rdquo; including &ldquo;legal advice&rdquo; is an element of the test for postponement.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Brooks v. Jackson</SOC><CITE>2009 BCCA 150</CITE><PARANUM>17</PARANUM></CASEREF>; <CASEREF><SOC>Wirtanen v. British Columbia</SOC><CITE>1994 CanLII 1109</CITE><COURTJUR>BCSC</COURTJUR></CASEREF>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>42. Under s. 8 of the <EM>New Act</EM>, a claim is not discoverable until a plaintiff &ldquo;knew or reasonably ought to have known&rdquo; that, among other things, &ldquo;a court proceeding would be an appropriate means to seek to remedy&rdquo; the claimed injury. In order to satisfy this criterion, the Common Plea explicitly identifies legal advice as the element that allowed the plaintiffs to ascertain and assess their legal rights in Canada&rdquo;.</P>
<P>43. Whether the <EM>Old Act</EM> or the <EM>New Act</EM> applies (or whether Eritrean law applies) has not been determined. That is a matter for trial. Under either statute, and on these pleadings, the information conveyed at the first meeting with counsel is material.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><N>F.</N><TI><UNDER>Implied waiver cases relied on by the plaintiffs do not alter the law concerning postponement</UNDER></TI>
<P>44. The cases on which the plaintiffs rely do not deal with waiver of privilege effected by a plea of postponement. These cases do not alter the fact that the plaintiffs' pleadings expressly assert that Canadian legal advice was the element that led the plaintiffs to discover a potential claim against Nevsun.</P>
<P>45. In <EM>Soprema</EM>, the plaintiff sued in negligent misrepresentation. Critically, the plaintiff never pleaded or otherwise referred to legal advice it received. It had not &ldquo;<UNDER>voluntarily</UNDER> made its understanding of its legal position a material issue in the litigation&rdquo;.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Soprema</EM>, para, 6. [Emphasis added.]</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> But legal advice may still have been relevant to its &ldquo;state of mind&rdquo; on the question of reasonable reliance. This Court ruled that a party must voluntarily inject legal advice it received or its understanding of the law before waiver is implied. A bare plea of misrepresentation was not enough.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Soprema</EM>, paras. 49, 51.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>46. In <EM>HMB</EM>, &ldquo;HMB did not plead that at it had relied on solicitors' advice to explain its conduct. The affidavit filed in support of its position did not assert reliance on solicitors' advice in defending its position.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>HMB</EM>, para. 45.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> In those circumstances, this Court held that the judge erred in inferring that legal advice must have been relevant and relied upon.</P>
<P>47. In short, <EM>Soprema</EM> clarified the specific issue of implied waiver in cases where the cause of action advanced, as opposed to any conduct on the part of a plaintiff, brings into issue the plaintiff's state of mind and its reliance on a representation. <EM>HMB</EM> follows this law. But neither case changes the law of implied waiver more broadly.</P>
<P>48. The plaintiffs' reliance on <EM>Soprema</EM> and <EM>HMB</EM> also overlooks the fact that they admitted in the court below that privilege had been waived by their plea of postponement. The only issue was the scope of that waiver.</P>
<P>49. The decisions that deal with postponement, <EM>Camosun</EM> and <EM>Harry</EM>, are consistent with other judgments dealing with implied waiver of privilege based on reliance on legal advice. In <CASEREF><SOC>S. &amp; K. Processors Ltd. v. Campbell Ave. Herring Producers Ltd.</SOC></CASEREF>, for example, Justice McLachlin (then in the Supreme Court of British Columbia) agreed that &ldquo;where a litigant relies on legal advice as an element of his claim or defence, the privilege which would otherwise attach to that advice is lost.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>S. &amp; K. Processors Ltd. v. Campbell Ave. Herring Producers Ltd.</SOC><CITE>[1983] B.C.J. No. 1499</CITE><PARANUM>6</PARANUM><COURTJUR>S.C.</COURTJUR></CASEREF> (&ldquo;<EM>S. &amp;. K.</EM>&rdquo;).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>50. In any case, the Common Plea satisfies the three-part test the plaintiffs say emerges from <EM>Soprema</EM> and <EM>HMB</EM> and subsequent cases from the Supreme Court of British Columbia. First, a plea of postponement or discoverability puts in issue the plaintiffs' mind. Second, the Common Plea expressly states that the plaintiffs received legal advice relating to their rights in Canada against Nevsun. Third, and most importantly, the plaintiffs rely on that legal advice as the event that took them from a state of ignorance to a state of knowledge about their legal rights, including that &ldquo;a court action in the courts of British Columbia was the appropriate means of seeking a remedy against Nevsun&rdquo;. The plaintiffs volunteered this information to obtain the benefit of postponement so that their claim against Nevsun would not be statute-barred. They cannot avoid the consequences of that decision.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><N>G.</N><TI><UNDER>Fairness requires disclosure to test the validity of the claim of postponement</UNDER></TI>
<P>51. The plaintiffs seek to shield the very information they say postponed their claim against Nevsun, including critical facts and advice they say were important to their ability to bring a claim against Nevsun.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>S. &amp; K.</EM>, para. 6; <EM>E-Pro</EM>, paras. 28, 39; <EM>Camosun</EM>, para. 19; <CASEREF><SOC>Souter v. 375561 B.C. Ltd.</SOC><CITE>[1995] B.C.J. No. 2265</CITE><PARANUM>22</PARANUM><COURTJUR>C.A.</COURTJUR></CASEREF>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Without knowing what information was exchanged at the first meeting, Nevsun has no means to test the postponement plea or to investigate what information or advice was available to the plaintiffs at earlier dates. Nevsun should be permitted to inquire into the legal knowledge acquired by the plaintiffs to test whether they could have obtained it earlier, or whether they in fact had such knowledge earlier.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Harry BCSC</EM>, para. 19.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>52. Fairness and consistency require that the defendant be permitted to explore the validity of the postponement plea:
<QUOTE><P>[T]here is always some manifestation of a <UNDER>voluntary intention</UNDER> to waive the privilege <UNDER>at least to a limited extent</UNDER>. The law then says that in fairness and consistency, it must be entirely waived. ... the plaintiff chose to raise the issue. <UNDER>Having raised it, he could not in fairness be permitted to use privilege to prevent his opponent exploring its validity</UNDER>.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>S. &amp; K.</EM>, para. 10.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> [Underlining added.]</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>53. It is particularly important for Nevsun to be permitted to test the validity of postponement claims because of the number of actions, the number of plaintiffs, and the number of alleged meetings with counsel. In ten actions, commenced over several years, approximately 80 plaintiffs make almost identical postponement pleas relying on legal advice obtained in different meetings between 2013 and 2018. Without knowing what occurred at these meetings, Nevsun cannot know whether it would have been possible for the plaintiffs to have obtained similar information through other sources, including Ms. Chyrum, other plaintiffs, other lawyers, family members or various media.</P>
<P>54. The case management judge was alive to the unfairness and inconsistency arising from the maintenance of the privilege in these circumstances. His decision that the plaintiffs' waiver includes information from the first meeting reveals no error of fact or law in the exercise of his discretion.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Dodek at 7.113-7.114, citing <CASEREF><SOC>R. v. Campbell</SOC><CITE>[1999] 1 S.C.R. 565</CITE><PARANUM>69&ndash;71</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><N>H.</N><TI><UNDER>The scope of the waiver is not overly broad</UNDER></TI>
<P>55. The case management judge's decision is founded on the language of the plaintiffs' own pleadings. They chose to put into issue the legal advice they received. Given the language of the Common Plea, the plaintiffs cannot now limit the communications and documents subject to disclosure as a result of the waiver.</P>
<P>56. The plaintiffs say that the scope of the order extends beyond the relevant &ldquo;subject matter&rdquo;. They submit that the only &ldquo;subject matter&rdquo; that is relevant is &ldquo;whether the claims were discoverable before the plaintiffs met Canadian counsel&rdquo;.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Appellants' Factum, para. 56.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The plaintiffs' attempt to limit the scope of the waiver is inconsistent with their admission that the waiver included everything preceding the first meeting with counsel and with the open-ended words used in the Common Plea.</P>
<P>57. Having pleaded reliance on advice imparted at a meeting with counsel as the basis for postponement and deliberately casting the net of that pleading broadly, the plaintiffs cannot now seek to limit disclosure to those communications that they say relate only to the discrete issue of postponement. It would be impractical to attempt to disentangle the information exchanged at that meetings in order to isolate those communications the plaintiffs say are relevant to postponement alone. It is unrealistic to expect that communications between the plaintiffs and their counsel could be unravelled in this way. Where privilege is waived, the scope of production includes &ldquo;any communication that has a relevant and material connection to the issue&rdquo;; the privilege is &ldquo;lost with respect to all communications on that topic, not just the ones that [the party] selects for disclosure.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Transportation Lease Systems Inc. v. Virdi</SOC><CITE>2007 BCSC 132</CITE><PARANUM>26</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> This includes any communication between solicitor and client regarding the subject matter of the legal advice, including background facts and communications necessary to put that advice into context.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>578115 Ontario Inc. v. Sears Canada Inc.</SOC><CITE>2013 ONSC 4135</CITE><PARANUM>40</PARANUM></CASEREF>; <CASEREF><SOC>Jack v. Canada</SOC><CITE>[2004] O.J. No. 3294</CITE><PARANUM>123, 128</PARANUM><COURTJUR>Sup. Ct. J.</COURTJUR></CASEREF>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>58. The plaintiffs' attempt to narrow the scope of the waiver to advice about postponement is contrary to the language of the Common Plea itself. This narrow approach would also give the plaintiffs the unilateral power to select what information to disclose. On the plaintiffs' theory, they would disclose only communications that relate to postponement of the limitation period. They would not have to disclose any other information that ostensibly led the plaintiffs to &ldquo;discover&rdquo; claims against Nevsun. This would prevent Nevsun from exploring whether any of that information was available to the plaintiffs at an earlier date.</P>
<P>59. The plaintiffs' approach is also contrary to the case management judge's objective of providing the parties with guidance going forward. This Court should not override the case management judge's assessment of what fairness and consistency require in the circumstances. The scope of the waiver ordered by the case management judge is consistent with the pleadings and demonstrates no error.</P>
<P>60. The plaintiffs also argue that the scope of the order is too broad because it is unmoored to the discovery process. With respect, Nevsun's application was necessarily general because (a) the plaintiffs had failed to produce lists of documents that included a proper listing of documents over which privilege had been claimed; and (a) on examinations for discovery of the plaintiffs, their counsel objected broadly to questions about discovery of their claims including meetings with Canadian counsel. The case management judge made his orders to provide guidance going forward.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>AR, Tab 16, Reasons, paras. 110-111.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>61. The case management judge's interlocutory rulings do not compromise trial fairness. Whether the information produced by the plaintiffs as a result of these orders is ultimately admitted at trial is for the trial judge to determine.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Do Process</EM>, para. 32.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> In the meantime, Nevsun should be permitted to investigate the plaintiffs' postponement claims.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><N>I.</N><TI><UNDER>The plaintiffs failed to establish that Ms. Chyrum's retainer is covered by litigation privilege</UNDER></TI>
<P>62. The case management judge made no error in ordering production of particulars of Ms. Chyrum's retainer. The plaintiffs failed to adduce sufficient evidence to establish such information was or could be subject to litigation privilege.</P>
<P>63. Litigation privilege is a limited exception to the principle of full disclosure. It is not an equal partner of the broadly interpreted solicitor-client privilege. More information is required to justify the invocation litigation privilege than for solicitor-client privilege.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Gichuru v. British Columbia (Information and Privacy Commissioner)</SOC><CITE>2014 BCCA 259</CITE><PARANUM>33</PARANUM></CASEREF> (&ldquo;<EM>Gichuru</EM>&rdquo;), and cases cited therein.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>64. An agreement between counsel and a third party may be subject to litigation privilege in some cases. However, the question is whether the party asserting the privilege can satisfy the test for litigation privilege in connection with a particular document. A party asserting litigation privilege over a particular document has the burden to show that (1) litigation was ongoing or was reasonably contemplated &ldquo;at the time the document was created&rdquo;; and (2) the dominant purpose of creating the document was to prepare for that litigation.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Gichuru</EM>, para. 32.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>65. Litigation privilege belongs to the litigant.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Blank v. Canada (Minister of Justice)</SOC><CITE>2006 SCC 39</CITE><PARANUM>32</PARANUM></CASEREF>; <CASEREF><SOC>Mask v. Silvercorp Metals Inc.</SOC><CITE>2014 ONSC 5727</CITE><PARANUM>29</PARANUM></CASEREF>, citing <CASEREF><SOC>St. Lewis v. Rancourt</SOC><CITE>2013 ONSC 3334</CITE></CASEREF>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> If counsel or third parties are contemplating litigation, but there is no evidence of the involvement of any litigant at that time, litigation privilege cannot attach.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Hoy v. Medtronic</SOC><CITE>2001 BCSC 944</CITE><PARANUM>55-56</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>66. The plaintiffs here failed to establish that litigation privilege applied to Ms. Chyrum's retainer. In response to Nevsun's application for a ruling on objections relating to Ms. Chyrum, plaintiffs' counsel provided an unfiled affidavit which stated (for the first time in this litigation) that Ms. Chyrum had been an agent of counsel since May 1, 2013, who recruited and communicated with witnesses and clients.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>AAB, Tab 4, Lascaris Affidavit, para. 3.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> No other evidence was proffered about Ms. Chyrum's circumstances. In particular, there was no evidence from any plaintiff.</P>
<P>67. Litigation privilege cannot attach to Ms. Chyrum's retainer because, on the plaintiffs' own pleadings, no plaintiff had retained or even met with counsel in May of 2013. The plaintiffs in the Araya Action say they first met counsel in early December 2013. The next meeting took place in June 2014, and continuing thereafter. Litigation could not have been in contemplation at the time of Ms. Chyrum's retainer because there were no clients to contemplate litigation.</P>
<P>68. In addition, the evidence adduced by the plaintiffs did not provide sufficient information to establish that Ms. Chyrum's retainer is covered by the privilege. There was insufficient evidence to establish that the retainer's dominant purpose was to prepare for litigation given Ms. Chyrum's multiple, overlapping roles before and during this litigation.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Gichuru</EM>, paras. 31-32. See also e.g. <CASEREF><SOC>Kitsul v. Slater Vecchio LLP</SOC><CITE>2015 BCSC 1394</CITE><PARANUM>40</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>69. The decision to order disclosure or Ms. Chyrum's retainer is not unfair. In the first place, Nevsun raised the issue of the privilege attaching to communications and documents with Ms. Chyrum and the plaintiffs. It sought rulings on objections made on discovery, including objections in which litigation privilege was claimed.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>AR, Tab 13, NOA, Part 1, paras. 4, 6; Part 3, 14, 22.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Second, the plaintiffs agreed that privilege had been waived over communications and documents before the first meeting with counsel as a result of pleading postponement. The case management judge correctly recognized that his ruling would resolve many requests and objections regarding the plaintiffs' dealings with Ms. Chyrum. Third, Nevsun had raised the issue of Ms. Chyrum's multiple roles in the litigation. The plaintiffs were well aware that Ms. Chyrum's status was in issue.</P>
<P>70. Given Ms. Chyrum's fluid roles in this case, disclosure of the retainer is necessary to help delineate the capacity in which she may have been acting when communicating with the plaintiffs. The case management judge's decision to order production of information related to Ms. Chyrum's retainer was a reasonable exercise of his discretion as a case management judge regarding disclosure of documents.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><N>J.</N><TI><UNDER>Conclusion</UNDER></TI>
<P>71. The case management judge did not err in finding that the plaintiffs admitted waiver of privilege included documents and communications exchanged in the first meeting with counsel. No other conclusion is possible on a plain reading of the Common Plea. The decision is in keeping with established principles concerning postponement and waiver of privilege. The case management judge did not err in ordering disclosure of Ms. Chyrum's retainer.</P></BLOCK2></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="VI">PART 4&mdash;NATURE OF ORDER SOUGHT</TI>
<P>72. That the appeal be dismissed with costs.</P>
<P>All of which is respectfully submitted.</P>
<P>Dated at the City of Vancouver, Province of British Columbia, this 7th day of May, 2019.</P>
<P>&ellip35; Andrew I. Nathanson</P>
