<BLOCK2><TI><EM>Nevsun Attempts to Recast the Evidence and the Pleadings</EM></TI>
<P>1. Throughout its factum, Nevsun attempts to recast the plaintiffs' pleadings in order to make the case that the plaintiffs' pleadings rely on legal advice, a conclusion the chambers judge never drew himself.</P>
<P>2. At paragraph 28 of its factum, Nevsun's (unattributed) quotation of the plaintiffs' reply pleadings erroneously quotes the reply as stating that &ldquo;[p]rior to assessing legal advice...&rdquo;. None of the reply pleadings include this statement. Instead, the pleadings state that the plaintiffs lacked the means to discover that they may have a claim against Nevsun &ldquo;prior to <UNDER>accessing</UNDER> legal advice&rdquo; (emphasis added).<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Respondent's Factum at para 28.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>3. Nevsun also claims that the plaintiffs could have&mdash;but did not&mdash;rely on &ldquo;challenging personal circumstances&rdquo; as a reason for postponement. But in the portions of the reply pleading in the <CASEREF><SOC>Daniel Mekonen et al. v. Nevsun Resources Ltd.</SOC></CASEREF> (&ldquo;Mekonen Action&rdquo;) that Nevsun does not reproduce in its factum, the pleadings do exactly this. The reply explains why the plaintiffs could not discover the claims sooner by particularizing these challenging circumstances. These circumstances include:</P>
<P>(a) &ldquo;Eritrea lacks a functioning legal system through which the plaintiffs could vindicate their legal rights against Nevsun;&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Reply in <CASEREF><SOC>Mekonen et al v. Nevsun Resources Ltd.</SOC><JUDGDATE>filed May 25, 2018</JUDGDATE><DOCKET>SCBC Action No.S-184108</DOCKET></CASEREF> (&ldquo;Mekonen Reply&rdquo;) at para 12(a), Appeal Record (&ldquo;AR&rdquo;), at Tab 11.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>(b) &ldquo;Eritrea lacks lawyers willing to take on the claims of the plaintiffs;&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Mekonen Reply at para 12(b), AR, Tab 11.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>(c) [with respect to plaintiff Ftsum Mehari] &ldquo;Traveled from Ethiopia to Kenya in February 2017, to care for his brother who suffers from schizophrenia and cannot work. Mr. Mehari has earned approximately CAD $200 per month at times since arriving in Kenya but must provide for his brother financially. As such, in Kenya, Mr. Mehari continued to lack the means to ascertain and assess his legal rights in Canada as against the defendant and could not do so until he met with Canadian counsel on January 21, 2018&rdquo;;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Mekonen Reply at para 27(c), AR, Tab11.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>(d) [with respect to Plaintiff Semere Mebrahtom] &ldquo;Left Ethiopia for Europe in or about October 2015, via Sudan, Uganda, Sudan again, and then Turkey. After several unsuccessful attempts to travel from Turkey to Greece by migrant vessel, he arrived in Greece in or about March 2017. From there, he made his way to Germany, arriving and seeking asylum in or about August 2017. While he traveled, he did not have the means to nor could he ascertain and assess his legal rights in Canada against the defendant&rdquo;;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Mekonen Reply at para 32(c), AR, Tab 11.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> and</P>
<P>(e) [with respect to Plaintiff Merde Araya] &ldquo;Left Ethiopia for Europe via Sudan and Egypt in or about May 2012. He was again detained in Egypt, this time for approximately 14 months. On release from detention he was deported again to Ethiopia, in or about July 2013. During this period of travel, detention in Egypt, and deportation from Egypt, he lacked the means to ascertain and assess his legal rights in Canada as against the defendant.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Mekonen Reply at para 37(d), AR, Tab 11.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>4. Another example of Nevsun's attempt to recast the reply as being based on legal advice is its assertion that the plaintiffs claim that they &ldquo;obtained legal advice during a particular meeting with Canadian counsel, at which time they &ldquo;ascertained and assessed&rdquo; their legal rights to bring a claim against Nevsun.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Respondent's Factum at para 26.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> This is an inaccurate rephrasing of para. 14(b) of the reply pleading in the Mekonen Action, which actually states that:
<QUOTE><P>[Plaintiff Daniel Mekonen] Fled Eritrea to Ethiopia in or about February 2011, where he has been restricted to a refugee camp by Ethiopian authorities and under a legal restriction on the right to work applicable to refugees in Ethiopia such that, in addition to the general reasons stated in paragraph 11, he lacked the financial means to ascertain and assess his legal rights in Canada as against the defendant and could not do so until he met with Canadian counsel on January 16, 2018.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Mekonen Reply at para 14(b), AR, Tab 11.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></QUOTE></P>
<P>5. A plea that a plaintiff was unable to ascertain and assess his legal rights because he lacked the financial means to do so <UNDER>before</UNDER> meeting with Canadian counsel is not equivalent to saying that legal advice was &ldquo;obtained&rdquo; on a particular date at which time the plaintiff &ldquo;ascertained and assessed&rdquo; his legal rights.</P>
<P>6. The plaintiffs do not point to legal advice &ldquo;received in their first meeting as the triggering event to answer a limitation defence&rdquo;, as Nevsun asserts.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Respondent's Factum at para 29.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Instead&mdash;as the pleadings explain&mdash;the plaintiffs' circumstances were such that they were unable to ascertain and assess their legal rights until they were able to meet with Canadian lawyers. This is vastly different from a claim that particular legal advice triggered the discovery of a claim.</P>
<P>7. Another example of Nevsun's efforts to recharacterize the record is its statement that the affidavit of Mr. Dimitri Lascaris discloses that Ms. Elizabeth Chyrum &ldquo;recruited and communicated with witnesses and clients&rdquo;.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Respondent's Factum at para 66.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The affidavit of Mr. Lascaris states that Ms. Chyrum was retained to &ldquo;communicate&rdquo; with clients and potential clients&mdash;not &ldquo;recruit&rdquo; them. Once again, Nevsun advances vague assertions of impropriety that lack evidentiary foundation.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI><EM>The Declaration Below is Overly Broad</EM></TI>
<P>8. In stating that it will be up to the trial judge to determine the admissibility of the information required to be produced if the order below is upheld,<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Respondent's Factum at para 61.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Nevsun makes a concession that is not evident from the face of the order. The chambers judge did not limit the declaration of waiver to the discovery process. It applies broadly to &ldquo;all communications and documents&rdquo; across ten related actions without this qualification. Because the order is not limited to the discovery process, the chambers judge's broad declaration would appear to continue to apply at trial without this concession.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI><EM>Nevsun's Attempts to Artificially Confine the Leading Cases on Implied Waiver</EM></TI>
<P>9. In its factum, Nevsun seeks to restrict the precedential value of Mr. Justice Harris's decision in <CASEREF><SOC>Soprema Inc. v. Wolrige Mahon LLP</SOC></CASEREF><FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Soprema Inc. v. Wolrige Mahon LLP</SOC><CITE>2016 BCCA 471</CITE></CASEREF> (&ldquo;<EM>Soprema</EM>&rdquo;).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> by making the rather remarkable assertion that the decision is only directed at &ldquo;cases where the cause of action advanced, as opposed to any conduct on the part of a plaintiff, brings into issue the plaintiffs state of mind and its reliance on a representation&rdquo; and that it did not change the law on implied waiver more broadly.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Respondent Factum at para 47.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>10. This assertion is not supported by this Court's recent decision in <CASEREF><SOC>HMB Holdings Limited v. Replay Resorts Inc.</SOC></CASEREF>, which applies <EM>Soprema</EM> in circumstances where the defendant claimed that the plaintiff had waived privilege by providing certain evidence in an affidavit&mdash;not by advancing a misrepresentation claim.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>HMB Holdings Limited v. Replay Resorts Inc.</SOC><CITE>2018 BCCA 273</CITE></CASEREF> (&ldquo;<EM>HMB</EM>&rdquo;), at paras 20-21.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Mr. Justice Hunter concluded that the chambers judge's finding of waiver was inconsistent with first principles of solicitor-client privilege (set out in <EM>Soprema</EM>) and the &ldquo;principles set out by this Court in <EM>Doman</EM> and <EM>Soprema</EM>&rdquo;.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>HMB</EM> at paras 30&ndash;32; see also paras 40&ndash;47 where it is evident that <EM>Soprema</EM> is the leading case in BC on implied waiver of privilege.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Clearly, the division that decided <EM>HMB</EM> did not consider <EM>Soprema</EM> to only be relevant to allegations of waiver based on the plaintiff's chosen cause of action.</P>
<P>11. Further, Nevsun's attempt to narrow and distinguish <EM>Soprema</EM> and <EM>HMB</EM> is undermined by its reliance on what it says is a critical distinction&mdash;that the plaintiff in <EM>Soprema</EM> &ldquo;never pleaded or otherwise referred to legal advice it received.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Respondent Factum at para 45.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> This argument is directly undermined by <EM>HMB</EM>, which quotes with approval a passage from <CASEREF><SOC>Creative Career Systems Inc. v. Ontario</SOC></CASEREF>,<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>HMB</EM> at paras 43-44.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> This passage explicitly states that disclosure by a party that it received legal advice&mdash;or even an admission that it relied on legal advice&mdash;does not waive privilege.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Creative Career Systems Inc. v. Ontario</SOC><CITE>2012 ONSC 649</CITE><PARANUM>31</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> <EM>HMB</EM> concludes that in both that case and <EM>Soprema</EM>, the plaintiffs did not &ldquo;plead that it had relied on solicitors' advice to explain its conduct&rdquo;.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>HMB</EM> at para 45.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The critical issue is whether the plaintiff has pleaded <UNDER>reliance</UNDER> on legal advice to explain its conduct&mdash;not whether the pleadings refer to the plaintiff as having received legal advice.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI><EM>The Date Ms. Chyrum Was Initially Retained is Immaterial to the Errors Made Below</EM></TI>
<P>12. Nevsun's submission that litigation privilege does not attach to Ms. Chyrum's retainer because she was initially retained before Canadian counsel first met the plaintiffs is flawed for several reasons.</P>
<P>13. First, the order under appeal does not limit the production of documents relating to Ms. Chyrum's retainer to the period before counsel's first meeting with any of the plaintiffs. It presumably also captures documents relating to her continuing retainer as an agent engaged to communicate with clients and witnesses in the actions.</P>
<P>14. Second, <CASEREF><SOC>Hoy v. Medtronic</SOC></CASEREF><FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Hoy v. Medtronic</SOC><CITE>2001 BCSC 944</CITE></CASEREF> (&ldquo;<EM>Hoy</EM>&rdquo;).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> does not stand for the general proposition that litigation privilege can never attach to communications between counsel and third parties prior to the client actually retaining counsel. Otherwise, counsel could never investigate claims before being retained as investigative steps taken (such as consulting experts, interviewing witnesses etc.) in anticipation of a meeting with a prospective client and a retainer would not be privileged.</P>
<P>15. <EM>Hoy</EM> considered whether documents that existed before the representative plaintiff contemplated litigation, which related to the financial arrangement between a law firm and US consulting lawyers, were privileged.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Hoy</EM> at paras 57.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Madam Justice Kirkpatrick emphasized that the sought-after documents (which were still not producible, since they were irrelevant) were not made to aid in the conduct of the litigation.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Hoy</EM> at para 21, 57.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> This distinguishes the situation here, where counsel retained an agent to communicate with potential clients&mdash;in circumstances where there was a language barrier&mdash;before first meeting the clients and being retained.</P>
<P>Date: May 10, 2019</P>
<P>&ellip35; Signature of lawyer for the Appellants</P>
<P>Reidar Mogerman</P></BLOCK2></BLOCK1>
