<BLOCK0><TI>MEMORANDUM OF ARGUMENT</TI>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="I"><UNDER>PART 1&mdash;STATEMENT OF FACTS</UNDER></TI>
<BLOCK2><TI><EM>Overview</EM></TI>
<P>1. The plaintiffs are refugees who have fled the repressive regime of Eritrea. In the underlying actions, they allege that the defendant was complicit in the use of their forced labour to construct the Bisha mine. In this proposed appeal, the plaintiffs seek to appeal the chamber judge's declaration that, through pleading that any applicable limitation periods were postponed until they had access to the legal counsel necessary to discover their claims, the plaintiffs have implicitly waived privilege over communications and documents relating to their first meeting with Canadian counsel. They also seek to appeal the chamber judge's order that they produce the details of their counsel's engagement of a third party, Ms. Elizabeth Chyrum, retained to communicate with the plaintiffs in relation to the litigation.</P>
<P>2. The chamber judge's broad declarations of waiver of privilege and his order that the plaintiffs produce details of Ms. Chyrum's retainer are not based in a particular part of the <EM>Supreme Court Civil Rules</EM>. As these broad, ungrounded declarations are made uniformly across multiple related actions, they are not limited appeal orders within the meaning of the <EM>Court of Appeal Rules</EM>. An appeal lies as of right.</P>
<P>3. Alternatively, if leave to appeal is required, leave is justified. The plaintiffs' proposed appeal raises serious issues concerning the correct application of the principles of waiver of privilege as they apply to pleadings of postponement. The decision below is significant and far-reaching in relation to the litigation and the practice as a whole. The interests of justice warrant an appeal.</P>
<P>4. The plaintiffs also seek a stay of execution of the order below until the proposed appeal is finally deposed of. Since the filing of the plaintiffs' original motion book, Nevsun has indicated that it will consent to a stay of execution pending appeal if the proposed appeal is allowed to proceed to a hearing on its merits.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI><EM>Background</EM></TI>
<P>5. The plaintiffs in this action (the &ldquo;Araya Action&rdquo;) allege that the defendant, Nevsun Resources Ltd. (&ldquo;Nevsun&rdquo;), entered into a commercial venture with the Government of Eritrea to develop the Bisha mine in Eritrea. They allege that they were forced to work on the mine's construction under the constant threat of physical punishment, torture and imprisonment. The plaintiffs allege that Nevsun was complicit in the use of forced labour, slavery, torture, inhuman treatment and crimes against humanity.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Araya v. Nevsun Resources</SOC><CITE>2017 BCCA 401</CITE><PARANUM>1&ndash;7</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>6. The Araya Action was originally framed as a proposed representative proceeding. After the chambers judge granted Nevsun's application challenging this form of proceeding in 2016, however, nine additional related actions were filed and served.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Affidavit #1 of Kimberly Hill, made February 12, 2019 (&ldquo;Hill #1&rdquo;), Motion Book (&ldquo;MB&rdquo;), Tab 16, at para 2.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> There are currently ten actions involving 85 plaintiffs under the common judicial management of the chambers judge, Mr. Justice Abrioux (the &ldquo;Related Actions&rdquo;).<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Hill #1, MB, Tab 16, at paras 3, 4, 11.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> A six month trial in the Araya Action is set to begin on April 6, 2020.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Hill #1, MB, Tab 16, at para 12.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>7. In reply to Nevsun's responses to civil claim, the plaintiffs have pleaded in each of the Related Actions that the actions are not subject to any limitation period. In the alternative, however, the plaintiffs plead that any limitation period applicable was postponed until at least the time when each of the plaintiffs accessed the legal advice of Canadian counsel necessary to ascertain and assess their legal rights in Canada against Nevsun.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>See e.g., Reply at para 1 in <CASEREF><SOC>Alemayo v. Nevsun Resources Ltd.</SOC><JUDGDATE>filed February 9, 2018</JUDGDATE><DOCKET>SCBC Action No. S169522</DOCKET></CASEREF> MB, Tabs 3&ndash;11 [Replies].</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The plaintiffs plead that before these meetings, they lacked the means to discover that a court action in British Columbia was an appropriate way to seek a remedy against Nevsun.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>See e.g. Amended Reply at paras 8&ndash;11 in <CASEREF><SOC>Negash et al v. Nevsun Resources Ltd.</SOC><JUDGDATE>filed February 13, 2018</JUDGDATE><DOCKET>SCBC Action No. S-1610863</DOCKET></CASEREF> MB, Tab 9.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>8. Following delivery of the replies, Nevsunbrought an application alleging that by pleading postponement, the plaintiffs in each of the Related Actions had implicitly waived privilege over all communications and documents relating to the pursuit of the actions up until the date that each of the claims were filed.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Nevsun's Notice of Application, MB, Tab 12, at para 1.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> In addition, Nevsun sought other declarations of waiver of solicitor-client privilege, as well as declarations that all communications between and amongst the plaintiffs with other third parties involved in the coordination of the Related Actions were either not protected by solicitor-client privilege or alternatively that the plaintiffs had waived privilege over these communications.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Nevsun's Notice of Application, MB, Tab 12, at paras 2&ndash;5.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>9. Since Nevsun first raised the issue of waiver of privilege, the plaintiffs have not disputed that the postponement pleadings put into issue the plaintiffs' state of mind regarding the extent to which they had knowledge of the core ingredients of the lawsuit prior to first meeting Canadian counsel.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Affidavit #8 of Roxanne Dhanpaul, sworn December 12, 2018 (&ldquo;Dhanpaul #8&rdquo;), MB, Tab 13, Exhibits M and N.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Under s. 8 of the <EM>Limitation Act</EM>,<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Limitation Act</EM>, SBC 2012, c 13.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> the plaintiffs' claims are not discoverable until they knew or reasonably ought to have known of both the necessary material facts and that a court proceeding would be an appropriate means to seek a remedy against Nevsun for their injuries.</P>
<P>10. At the hearing, Nevsun narrowed its allegations ofwaiver due to postponement, other than in the Araya Action, to the time period leading up to and including the plaintiffs' first meeting with Canadian counsel. Nevsun also abandoned or did not pursue a number of its other claims.</P>
<P>11. In oral reasons, later released in writing, the chamber judge granted Nevsun's application in part.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Oral Reasons for Judgment of Mr. Justice Abrioux (<CASEREF><SOC>Araya et al v. Nevsun Resources Ltd.</SOC><CITE>2019 BCSC 260</CITE></CASEREF>) (&ldquo;Reasons&rdquo;), MB, Tab 1.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The chamber judge found that by pleading postponement, the plaintiffs in the Related Actions, other than the Araya Action, had waived privilege over solicitor-client communications up to, and including, the first meeting they had with counsel. As the plaintiffs indicated that they intended to apply to amend the pleadings in the Araya Action, the chamber judge adjourned Nevsun's application in relation to that action. The chamber judge ordered the plaintiffs to produce the documents over which privilege had been waived within 45 days of the date of the order.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Reasons, MB, Tab 1, at para 112.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>12. The chamber judge also ordered the plaintiffs in each of the Related Actions to disclose the particulars of their counsel's retainer of Ms. Chyrum.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Reasons, MB, Tab 1, at para 112.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Ms. Chyrum is an agent of counsel who is retained to communicate with clients and potential clients.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Affidavit #9 of Kimberly Hill, made December 21, 2018 (&ldquo;Hill #9&rdquo;), MB, Tab 15, at para 4.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Ms. Chyrum has previously served as a translator on some of the plaintiffs' affidavits, however, none of these affidavits were at issue on this application.</P>
<P>13. Following the delivery of the plaintiffs' original motion book, the parties agreed to adjourn the original scheduled hearing date to allow time for release of the written reasons. The parties agreed that if this Court finds either that leave to appeal is not required or grants leave to appeal, Nevsun will consent to a stay of execution of the order pending disposition of the appeal. If this Court dismisses the plaintiffs' application for leave to appeal, the parties agreed that the plaintiffs will produce the privileged documents within five working days.</P></BLOCK2></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="II"><UNDER>PART 2&mdash;POINTS IN ISSUE</UNDER></TI>
<P>14. This motion raises the following issues:
<P1>(a) whether a broad declaration of waiver of privilege, not limited to an order under Rule 7-1 of the <EM>Supreme Court Civil Rules</EM>, may be appealed as of right; and</P1>
<P1>(b) if leave to appeal is required, whether it is the interests of justice to grant leave to appeal?</P1></P></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="III"><UNDER>PART 3&mdash;REASONS WHY LEAVE AND STAY SHOULD BE GRANTED</UNDER></TI>
<BLOCK2><TI><EM>The Appeal is as of Right</EM></TI>
<P>15. Under ss. 6 and 7 of the <EM>Court of Appeal Act</EM>, orders made by a judge of the Supreme Court may be appealed as of right unless another enactment limits this right of appeal or the order is a &ldquo;limited appeal order&rdquo;, as defined under Rule 2.1 of the <EM>Court of Appeal Rules</EM>, in which case leave to appeal is required.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Court of Appeal Act</EM>, RSBC 1996, c 77.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Leave to appeal is not required if multiple orders are made at the same time and some require leave to appeal while others do not.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Holly Brinton, <EM>Civil Appeal Handbook</EM> (Continuing Legal Education Society of British Columbia, March 2018) at p 3&ndash;5; <CASEREF><SOC>Royal Bank of Canada v. Miller</SOC><CITE>2012 BCCA 419</CITE><PARANUM>10</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>16. Rule 2.1 of the <EM>Court of Appeal Rules</EM> exhaustively lists the types of orders that qualify as limited appeal orders.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Yao v. Li</SOC><CITE>2012 BCCA 315</CITE><PARANUM>27</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The prescribed list of orders that require leave to appeal is interpreted narrowly and cannot be expanded by inference.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Wallman v. Gill</SOC><CITE>2013 BCCA 110</CITE><PARANUM>20</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> For a proposed appeal to require leave, the &ldquo;jurisdictional basis&rdquo; of the underlying order must be one of the types of orders listed under Rule 2.1.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Hu v. Ting</SOC><CITE>2017 BCCA 305</CITE><PARANUM>28-29</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>17. The focus is on the nature of the order, not its subject matter.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Clifford v. Lord</SOC><CITE>2013 BCCA 302</CITE><PARANUM>14</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> While a declaration of waiver of privilege over documents may qualify as a limited appeal order if the jurisdictional basis of the order is in Part 7 of the <EM>Supreme Court Civil Rules</EM>,<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Do Process LP v. Infokey Software Inc.</SOC><CITE>2014 BCCA 470</CITE><PARANUM>11</PARANUM></CASEREF> (&ldquo;<EM>Do Process</EM>&rdquo;). Rule 2.1(a)(ii) defines orders granting or refusing relief under Part 7 of the <EM>Supreme Court Civil Rules</EM>, other than orders under r 7-7, as &ldquo;limited appeal orders&rdquo;.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> leave may not be required if the jurisdictional basis of the order is found elsewhere.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>H.M.B. Holdings Limited v. Replay Resorts Inc.</SOC><CITE>2018 BCCA 8</CITE><PARANUM>12</PARANUM></CASEREF> (&ldquo;<EM>HMB Holdings</EM> Chambers&rdquo;)</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>18. Here, the chamber judge's declaration of waiver extends beyond the discovery process to broad declarations of waiver that presumably extends to all aspects of the Related Actions into trial. This plainly distinguishes the proposed appeal from <CASEREF><SOC>Do Process LP v Infokey Software Inc.</SOC></CASEREF>, where the declaration of waiver was limited to particular documents and the relief was sought under Rule 7-1 of the <EM>Supreme Court Civil Rules</EM>.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Do Process</EM> at paras 10-11.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Although Nevsun referenced Rule 7-1(12) in an earlier letter demanding access to counsel's file,<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Dhanpaul #8, MB, Tab 13, Exhibit M.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> neither the order, nor Nevsun's notice of application, identifies any part of the <EM>Supreme Court Civil Rules</EM> as the basis for the declaration.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Nevsun's Notice of Application, MB, Tab 12; Order Made After Application of Mr. Justice Abrioux, entered February 21, 2019 (&ldquo;Order&rdquo;), MB, Tab 2.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Unlike the order at issue in <EM>Do Process</EM>, the order below makes a stand-alone declaration of waiver independent of particular documents.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Do Process</EM> at para 10.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>19. Further, the chamber judge's order that the plaintiffs produce details of Ms. Chyrum's retainer appears to be unmoored from any issue in the pleadings that would justify production under Rule 7-1 or any other relevant rule of court.</P>
<P>20. Since the jurisdictional basis for the chamber judge's order is not under Part 7 of the <EM>Supreme Court Civil Rules</EM> (or any prescribed limited appeal order under Rule 2.1), it follows that the appeal may proceed as of right.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI><EM>Reasons Why Leave to Appeal Should be Granted</EM></TI>
<P>21. In any event, even if the order below is a limited appeal order, leave to appeal is justified.</P>
<P>22. The main considerations on an application for leave to appeal are:
<P1>(a) whether the point on appeal is of significance to the practice;</P1>
<P1>(b) whether the point raised is of significance to the action itself;</P1>
<P1>(c) whether the appeal is <EM>prima facie</EM> meritorious or, on the other hand, whether it is frivolous; and</P1>
<P1>(d) whether the appeal will unduly hinder the progress of the action.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Michael Wilson &amp; Partners, Ltd. v. Desir&ea;e Resources Inc.</SOC><CITE>2016 BCCA 296</CITE><PARANUM>17</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P1></P>
<P>23. The overarching question is whether granting leave to appeal is in the interests of justice.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Ibid</EM> at para 18.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<BLOCK3><TI>The Prospects of Success of the Proposed Appeal</TI>
<P>24. At this stage, the applicant is only required to show that the proposed appeal is not frivolous.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Windshield Doctor Canada Ltd. v. Glass Masters Ltd.</SOC><CITE>2005 BCCA 220</CITE><PARANUM>11</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>25. The plaintiffs' proposed appeal clearly meets this low threshold. If the appeal proceeds, the question of whether the court below correctly identified and applied the test for waiver of privilege is a question of law evaluated on a correctness standard.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Soprema Inc. Wolrige Mahon LLP</SOC><CITE>2016 BCCA 471</CITE><PARANUM>16</PARANUM></CASEREF> (&ldquo;<EM>Soprema</EM> Appeal&rdquo;).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The plaintiffs raise serious issues about the correctness of the chamber judge's articulation and application of these principles.</P>
<P>26. On the first ground of appeal, the plaintiffs intend to argue that the court below erred in law by finding that the plaintiffs have waived privilege over communications connected to their first meeting with Canadian counsel. As the plaintiffs have always acknowledged, the pleadings put in issue their state of mind prior to first meeting Canadian counsel, including the nature of any legal advice that may have informed this state of mind.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Dhanpaul #8, MB, Tab 12, Exhibit N.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> What is far from clear, however, is how the pleadings put in issue the plaintiffs' reliance on the legal advice they received at their first meeting with Canadian counsel.</P>
<P>27. Waiver of solicitor-client privilege requires more than a pleading that puts the privilege-holder's &ldquo;state of mind&rdquo; at issue<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Soprema</EM> Appeal at paras 52-53.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> In <CASEREF><SOC>Soprema Inc. v. Wolrige Mahon LLP</SOC></CASEREF>&rdquo;, this Court clarified that even though legal advice may be relevant to a privilege-holder's state of mind on a material issue, waiver can only be implied if the privilege-holder voluntarily injects the legal advice it received or its understanding of the law into the litigation.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Soprema</EM> Appeal at para 49; <CASEREF><SOC>H.M.B. Holdings Limited v. Replay Resorts Inc.</SOC><CITE>2018 BCCA 263</CITE><PARANUM>44</PARANUM></CASEREF> (&ldquo;<EM>HMB Holdings</EM> Appeal&rdquo;).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> As this Court stated recently in <CASEREF><SOC>H.M.B. Holdings Limited v. Replay Resorts Inc.</SOC></CASEREF>, &ldquo;[i]n the absence of either pleadings, evidence or argument asserting reliance on legal advice, [...] invocation of fairness and consistency are insufficient to ground waiver.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>HMB Holdings</EM> Appeal at para 47; Adam M. Dodek, <EM>Solicitor-Client Privilege</EM> (LexisNexis Canada Inc., 2014) at 7.143: &ldquo;Simply putting state of mind at issue without reliance on legal advice does not suffice for waiver&rdquo;.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>28. These authorities do not support the chamber judge's conclusion that the plaintiffs have waived privilege over their first meeting with counsel. The chamber judge failed to consider whether, by pleading postponement until they had access to legal advice of Canadian counsel, the plaintiffs actually invoked reliance on that legal advice.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>See Reasons, MB, Tab 1, at para 90.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>29. The content of the privileged communications exchanged at the first meeting with Canadian counsel is irrelevant to assessing the strength of the plaintiffs' pleas of postponement. No matter what advice they received during the first meeting, the communication contents do not shed light on whether the plaintiffs could have discovered earlier that a court action in British Columbia was an appropriate means of proceeding. In the absence of relevancy, it is difficult to see how the pleadings put in issue the plaintiffs' reliance on these communications.</P>
<P>30. Further, the chamber judge's order is unprecedented in the context of other decisions that have considered the relationship between pleadings of postponement and waiver of privilege. All of the cases Nevsun relied on below arose in contexts where postponement was sought for a period of time beyond the initial retainer of counsel.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Jack v. Canada (Attorney General)</SOC><CITE>[2004] O. J. No. 3294</CITE><PARANUM>114&ndash;124</PARANUM><COURTJUR>SCJ</COURTJUR></CASEREF>; <CASEREF><SOC>Harry v. British Columbia</SOC><CITE>2002 BCCA 557</CITE><PARANUM>5&ndash;9, 15</PARANUM></CASEREF>; <CASEREF><SOC>Camosun College v. Levelton Engineering Ltd.</SOC><CITE>2014 BCSC 1190</CITE><PARANUM>13&ndash;18, 25</PARANUM></CASEREF> (&ldquo;<EM>Camosun College</EM>&rdquo;).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> By pleading postponement past the date they retained counsel, the plaintiffs in these cases implicitly relied on a change in legal advice or in their counsel's knowledge as a basis for postponement. The same cannot be said here, where the plaintiffs do not contest that any applicable limitation period began to toll as soon as they had access to Canadian counsel.</P>
<P>31. The chamber judge also placed considerable weight on a 2014 journal article, in which the author argues that the time period over which privilege is waived should include the pleaded discovery date.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Reasons, MB, Tab 1, at para 80; Jonathan de Vries, &ldquo;<EM>Privilege and Limitations: The Impact of Raising the Discoverability of Claims on Solicitor-Client Privilege</EM>&rdquo;(2014) The Advocates Quarterly 43 at 252 (&ldquo;de Vries&rdquo;).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Neither of the two Ontario Superior Court of Justice decisions the author relied on for this point support this proposition as being_a broad rule of general application, particularly in situations such as the one here, where the plaintiffs do not plead postponement past the date they retained counsel.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Davenport v. Roughley Estate</SOC><CITE>2003 CarswellOnt 766</CITE><COURTJUR>SC</COURTJUR></CASEREF> (&ldquo;<EM>Davenport</EM>&rdquo;); <CASEREF><SOC>Lawless v. Anderson</SOC><CITE>2009 CanLII 58602</CITE><COURTJUR>ONSC</COURTJUR></CASEREF>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> In <CASEREF><SOC>Davenport v. Roughley Estate</SOC></CASEREF>, for example, the period of time over which Master Beaudoin found that privilege had been waived went up to, but did not include, the earliest possible pleaded triggering date for the start of the limitation period.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Davenport</EM> at paras 2, 9.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> In addition, the author's comments appear directed at situations where the plaintiff had access to a lawyer prior to the alleged discovery of the claim.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>See de Vries at 230.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>32. The plaintiffs' second proposed ground of appeal is that even if the plaintiffs implicitly waived privilege over some aspects of otherwise privileged communications relating to their first meeting with Canadian counsel, the chamber judge erred by making an overly broad declaration of waiver that goes beyond what is necessary to achieve a just result.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Camosun College</EM> at para 8.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The chamber judge's order that the waiver extends to all documents and communications relating to pursuit of the Related Actions and the claims they advance is not clearly limited to the issue of postponement.</P>
<P>33. As the Supreme Court of Canada has emphasized, solicitor-client privilege must be as close to absolute as possible.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Canada (Privacy Commissioner) v. Blood Tribe Department of Health</SOC><CITE>2008 SCC 44</CITE><PARANUM>9</PARANUM></CASEREF> (&ldquo;<EM>Blood Tribe</EM>&rdquo;)] <CASEREF><SOC>R. v. McClure</SOC><CITE>2001 SCC 14</CITE><PARANUM>35</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Any waiver of solicitor-client privilege should thus be construed narrowly, and privileged communications should be disclosed only to the extent absolutely necessary to achieve fairness.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Camosun College</EM> at para 31.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The waiver should therefore be limited to the specific matter put in issue by the postponement plea,<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Biehl v. Strang</SOC><CITE>2011 BCSC 213</CITE><PARANUM>65&ndash;67</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> that is whether the plaintiffs knew or ought to have known prior to meeting Canadian counsel that an action against Nevsun in Canada would be appropriate.</P>
<P>34. Lastly, the plaintiffs wish to appeal the chamber judge's order that they produce documents relating to the particulars of their counsel's engagement or retainer of Ms. Chyrum, who is retained as an agent of counsel to communicate with clients and potential clients.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Hill #9, MB, Tab 15, at para 4.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>35. The chamber judge's order that Ms. Chyrum's retainer be produced is not properly grounded in the context of this application. Instead, the order appears to be based on Nevsun's general assertion that Ms. Chyrum's role as agent of counsel and her work as a human rights activist raises the spectre of bias in her role as the translator of some of the plaintiffs' affidavits.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Reasons at para 109.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>36. Even if the information that Ms. Chyrum is retained to communicate with plaintiffs is relevant to this issue, the question of potential bias in Ms. Chyrum's translations does not arise on this application. Further, Nevsun's notice of application did not include a specific request for production of Ms. Chyrum's retainer and the plaintiffs did not rely on any of Ms. Chyrum's translations in responding to the application. The allegation that Ms. Chyrum's work as a human rights activist colours and invalidates her translations of some of the evidence should have been made in the context of a challenge to particular evidence, not as a general, free-standing assertion.</P>
<P>37. In addition, the plaintiffs intend to argue that the chamber judge erred by not considering whether the production of Ms. Chyrum's retainer would improperly intrude into litigation privilege. The details of a party's retainer of a third party consultant retained for the purposes of litigation fall plainly within the &ldquo;zone of privacy&rdquo; litigation privilege is intended to protect.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Blank v. Canada (Minister of Justice)</SOC><CITE>2006 SCC 39</CITE><PARANUM>28, 34</PARANUM></CASEREF>; J. Sopinka, S.N. Lederman and A. W. Bryant, <EM>The Law of Evidence in Canada</EM>, 5th ed (LexisNexis Canada Inc., March 2018), at 14.223.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>38. Like solicitor-client privilege, litigation privilege is not subject to a case-by-case balancing test.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Lizotte v. Aviva Insurance Company of Canada</SOC><CITE>2016 SCC 52</CITE><PARANUM>31</PARANUM></CASEREF> (&ldquo;<EM>Lizotte</EM>&rdquo;).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Where fundamental rules such as solicitor client or litigation privilege would otherwise shield the document from disclosure, it is not enough that the document may be relevant or that a general balancing of interests appears to favour disclosure.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Soprema</EM> Appeal at para 53; <EM>Lizotte</EM> at para 41.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The chamber judge failed to consider whether one of the defined exceptions to litigation privilege applied or whether the privilege had been waived. Instead, his reasons are limited to the issues of whether Ms. Chyrum's retainer is relevant to assessing her role in solicitor-client communications and Nevsun's general allegations of potential bias and impropriety (despite the lack of a specific pleading or evidentiary objection on this point).<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Reasons, MB, Tab 1, at paras 83, 107, 109.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI>The Importance of the Proposed Appeal to the Parties</TI>
<P>39. The proposed appealis clearly important to the partiesin each of the Related Actions. Solicitor-client privilege is &ldquo;jealously guarded&rdquo; for good reason.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Pritchard v. Ontario (Human Rights Commission)</SOC><CITE>2004 SCC 31</CITE><PARANUM>17</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> As Justice Binnie cautioned in <CASEREF><SOC>Canada (Privacy Commissioner) v. Blood Tribe Department of Health</SOC></CASEREF>, &ldquo;[e]xperience shows that people who have a legal problem will often not make a clean breast of the facts to a lawyer without an assurance of confidentiality &ldquo;as close to absolute as possible&rdquo;.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Blood Tribe</EM> at para 9.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The privilege is fundamentally important to the legal system and plays a key role in facilitating access to justice.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Alberta Information and Privacy Commissioner v. University of Calgary</SOC><CITE>2016 SCC 53</CITE><PARANUM>34</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> In this context, unwarranted intrusion into privileged communications has the potential to compromise the fairness of the eventual trials on the merits.</P>
<P>40. The chamber judge's broad declarations of waiver ofprivile across multiple related actions and to the claims of 85 plaintiffs. Whether or not this intrusion is justified in the circumstances is clearly a matter of importance in the litigation.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Soprema Inc. Wolrige Mahon LLP</SOC><CITE>2016 BCCA 309</CITE><PARANUM>8</PARANUM></CASEREF> (&ldquo;<EM>Soprema</EM> Chambers&rdquo;).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI>The Importance of the Appeal to the Practice</TI>
<P>41. The issue of when and how pleadings of postponementimp solicitor-client privilege is also significant to the profession generally. Clarification of uncertainty or confusion that may exist over the principles of solicitor-client and litigation privilege and the court's power to order waiver are recognized as important matters that warrant this Court's attention.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Soprema</EM> Chambers at para 6.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>42. The profession would benefit from clarification from this Court over how principles of implicit waiver apply in the context of pleadings of postponement that put in issue the plaintiff's state of mind but do not clearly invoke reliance on legal advice. As one commentator put it, waiver based on &ldquo;state of mind&rdquo; is &ldquo;the most confusing area of implied waiver jurisprudence.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Adam M. Dodek, <EM>Solicitor-Client Privilege</EM> (LexisNexis Canada Inc., 2014), at 7.131.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The issue of how the principles articulated in <EM>Soprema</EM> and <EM>HMB Holdings</EM> apply in the context of a plea of postponement is a significant issue to the practice as a whole.</P>
<P>43. Further, the interaction between waiver of privilege and a pleading of postponement based on a lack of access to legal advice (as opposed to one based on a lack of legal knowledge), is a novel circumstance in which the Court's guidance about the application of waiver in this context is relevant to the practice as a whole. As Justice Tysoe explained recently in the chambers decision in <CASEREF><SOC>H.M.B. Holdings Limited v. Replay Resorts Inc.</SOC></CASEREF>, &ldquo;waiver of solicitor-client privilege is a matter of significance to the profession generally because it is instructive to the profession to be aware of the situations in which privilege can be found to have been waived.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>HMB Holdings</EM> Chambers at para 14.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Guidance on when pleadings of postponement based on a lack of access to legal advice implicitly waive privilege over legal communications is beneficial to the profession generally.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI>The Utility of the Proposed Appeal and Whether the Appeal Would Cause Undue Delay</TI>
<P>44. As described above, the proposed appeal raises serious issues about whether the chamber judge properly articulated and applied principles of solicitor-client and litigation privilege and their waiver. These are significant and important issues to the plaintiffs.</P>
<P>45. In contrast, Nevsun will suffer little prejudice if leave to appeal is granted. Trial in the Araya Action is not set to begin until April 6, 2020.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Hill #1, MB, Tab 16, at para 12.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The plaintiffs are prepared to expedite the appeal. The proposed appeal raises discrete issues concerning several categories of privileged communications. According to the court's schedule of available dates for appeal hearings, there are multiple hearing dates currently available in April, May and June 2019.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Hill #1, MB, Tab 16, at para 17, Exhibit A.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The appeal can be heard well before the trial in the Araya Action is set to begin. Overall, the interests of justice weigh clearly in favour of granting leave to appeal.</P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI><EM>Reasons Why a Stay Should be Granted</EM></TI>
<P>46. The parties have agreed that if the proposed appeal proceeds to a hearing on its merits the order under appeal should be stayed until the appeal is finally disposed of.</P></BLOCK2></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="IV"><UNDER>PART 4&mdash;NATURE OF ORDER SOUGHT</UNDER></TI>
<P>47. The plaintiffs request the following relief:
<P1>(a) an order that the plaintiffs' notice of application for leave to appeal stand as a notice of appeal;</P1>
<P1>(b) alternately, an order that leave to appeal the chamber judge's order is granted;</P1>
<P1>(c) a stay of execution of the chamber judge's order pending final disposition of the appeal; and</P1>
<P1>(d) costs.</P1></P>
