<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="I">PART I: STATEMENT OF FACTS</TI>
<P>1. The plaintiffs' proposed appeal raises no point of principle requiring consideration by this Court. It is, instead, an attempt to challenge a case management judge's application of settled principles regarding the waiver of privilege that arises as a result of a plea of postponement in response to a limitation defence. The plaintiffs agreed there had been a waiver of privilege. The only question was the scope of that waiver. The defendant Nevsun Resources Ltd. (&ldquo;<BOLD>Nevsun</BOLD>&rdquo;) said, and the judge agreed, that the waiver included information exchanged at the plaintiffs' first meeting with counsel. The judge also agreed with Nevsun that the plaintiffs had to disclose the particulars of their retainer with a person who is now alleged to be an agent for the plaintiffs. The plaintiffs failed to establish that privilege attached to that retainer.</P>
<P>2. Fundamentally, these orders relate to the production of documents in a complex case-managed proceeding. Leave to appeal is required from such orders.</P>
<P>3. It is not in the interests of justice to grant leave to appeal. The plaintiffs' appeal merely takes issue with the judge's application of settled legal principles. An appeal would delay the progress of a complex, idiosyncratic proceeding where a number of ongoing and related interlocutory issues are currently before by the judge. It would disrupt ongoing discoveries set to take place around the world and the trial of the actions, the form of which is being determined by the judge.</P>
<BLOCK2><TI>Background</TI>
<P>4. The background to this case is summarized at paragraphs 4&ndash;13 of the judgment sought to be appealed.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Amended Motion Book (&ldquo;<BOLD>AMB</BOLD>&rdquo;), Tab 1, Oral Reasons for Judgment of Abrioux J., January 18, 2019 (&ldquo;<BOLD>Reasons</BOLD>&rdquo;).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> This is &ldquo;extremely complex&rdquo; litigation, which has been under judicial management by Abrioux J. since 2015. It involves ten actions and 85 plaintiffs, who allege the Bisha mine in Eritrea was built using forced labour by the Eritrean Government, the military, and its contractors. Nevsun denies all allegations. Abrioux J. recognized from the outset that the proceedings would be a &ldquo;challenge'' to manage and try, and would require &ldquo;extensive case management&rdquo;.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Araya v. Nevsun Resources Ltd.</SOC><CITE>2016 BCSC 1856</CITE><PARANUM>250, 292-293 and 571</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> That has been the case. The plaintiffs are resident in Ethiopia, Egypt, Kenya, Israel, France, Switzerland, Germany, Denmark, the Netherlands, the U.S., and Canada.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>Case Management and Related Orders</TI>
<P>5. In April 2018, the parties argued several applications, including whether test or &ldquo;bellwether&rdquo; cases should be selected and tried (the &ldquo;<BOLD>Bellwether Application</BOLD>&rdquo;). The parties entered into a consent order (the &ldquo;<BOLD>April 6 Order</BOLD>&rdquo;), which set deadlines for document discovery, permitted Nevsun to proceed with examinations for discovery of all plaintiffs subject to further order, and adjourned the Bellwether Application to 2019. As a placeholder pending determination of the Bellwether Application, Abrioux J. set a trial date in the Araya action &ldquo;for a minimum six month period to commence April 1, 2020&rdquo;. Abrioux J. explained that &ldquo;as these proceedings move forward&rdquo;, one of the &ldquo;key issues&rdquo; for the court to decide is whether Bellwether cases should be chosen as sought by the plaintiffs and, if so, which ones and on what issues, or whether the actions should be tried at the same time. He noted that &ldquo;[o]n either approach a significant amount of trial time will be required&rdquo;, with &ldquo;the ultimate trial time being up to two years&rdquo;.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Araya v. Nevsun Resources Ltd.</SOC><CITE>2018 BCSC 808</CITE><PARANUM>11, 40-41</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>6. Since the April 6 Order, Abrioux J. has held multiple judicial management conferences and heard numerous applications. In December 2018, Nevsun applied for orders that the plaintiffs produce documents and affidavits of documents. On January 21, 2019, in related reasons, Abrioux J. found that the plaintiffs' lists of documents were inadequate, and that the plaintiffs had not complied with document discovery orders and their obligations under the <EM>Supreme Court Civil Rules</EM> (&ldquo;<BOLD><EM>SCCR</EM></BOLD>&rdquo;). The judge ordered production of the requested documents, and ordered some plaintiffs to provide affidavits of documents. In making these orders, Abrioux J. noted that &ldquo;given that examinations for discovery are ongoing and the trial is in approximately 14 months, the actions are at a critical juncture ... the parties must expend considerable effort if there is any reasonable prospect for the trial to commence as scheduled.&rdquo; Abrioux J. added that the preparation for and hearing of the Bellwether application was a &ldquo;key intervening step&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Araya v. Nevsun Resources Ltd.</SOC><CITE>2019 BCSC 262</CITE><PARANUM>20-21</PARANUM></CASEREF> (&ldquo;<BOLD>Document Reasons</BOLD>&rdquo;). [Emphasis added.]</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>7. Abrioux J. also granted an order that Nevsun may conduct a further ten examinations by July 1, 2019 prior to the Beliwether Application. To that point, Nevsun had conducted seven examinations for discovery: two in the U.S., four in Europe, and one in B.C. The examinations have been difficult to arrange and all have required the use of interpreters. They were adjourned pending certain requests, rulings on objections (some of which were the subject of the application below), and further document discovery. Abrioux J. concluded that further discoveries were appropriate taking into account his knowledge of the case &ldquo;and the ongoing nature of the Bellwether applications and trial preparation and in particular, the need for the court to have a proper evidentiary record to consider the [Bellwether applications].&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Document Reasons, para. 39.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Since this decision, appointments to examine three of the plaintiffs have been delivered for April 22&ndash;30, 2019 in Addis Ababa, Ethiopia.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Reply Book, Tab 5, Affidavit of Gregory Berry, filed March 7, 2019, Exhibit &ldquo;K&rdquo;.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>8. On February 19, 2019, one of the plaintiffs, Abadi Alemayo, filed an application for leave to appeal Abrioux J.'s January 21, 2019 order that he list and produce documents relating to criminal proceedings against him in Switzerland.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>The Plaintiffs' Pleas of Postponement and Order Sought to be Appealed</TI>
<P>9. Nevsun's defences include that the plaintiffs' actions are statute-barred under Eritrean and B.C. law. In their Replies, the plaintiffs plead that the limitation period was &ldquo;postponed until at least the time when they accessed the legal advice of Canadian counsel to ascertain and assess their legal rights in Canada against Nevsun&rdquo;. They refer to the complexity of the legal issues and go on to assert that &ldquo;[p]rior to accessing the legal advice&rdquo; of Canadian counsel, they &ldquo;lacked the means to discover&rdquo; both that they had a claim against Nevsun and that an action in B.C. &ldquo;was the appropriate means of seeking a remedy against Nevsun&rdquo;. The plaintiffs plead that &ldquo;in order to ascertain and assess their legal rights against&rdquo; Nevsun, they &ldquo;required the benefit of legal advice from Canadian lawyers&rdquo;. The Araya plaintiffs alleged the limitation period applicable to their claims was postponed until the date the Araya action was commenced. The other plaintiffs pleaded postponement to the date of their first meeting with Canadian counsel.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>AMB, Tab 1, Reasons, paras. 63&ndash;67.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>10. Nevsun applied for an order that the plaintiffs produce documents over which privilege had been waived by virtue of the plea of postponement, as well as declarations that privilege had been waived. The declarations sought reflected Nevsun's position that the plaintiffs had not delivered lists of privileged documents i n compliance with Rule 7-1(7),<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>A step the plaintiffs have since agreed to take: Document Reasons, para. 33.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> preventing Nevsun from applying for specific documents.</P>
<P>11. Nevsun also applied for an order determining objections, mainly on the basis of solicitor-client privilege, made at the plaintiffs' examinations. Some of the objections related to communications with counsel prior to the date on which postponement was claimed. Others related to communications with Elsa Chryum. Ms. Chryum is an Eritrean human rights advocate. She has had diverse involvement with the plaintiffs, helping (as early as 2010) to locate counsel to bring an action against Nevsun; acting as a reference in asylum claims; serving as an interpreter for affidavits;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>A role which requires the interpreter to be objective and unbiased: <CASEREF><SOC>Luu v. Wang</SOC><CITE>2011 BCSC 1201</CITE><PARANUM>8&ndash;13</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> and, as disclosed for the first time at the hearing below, as of May 1, 2013, evidently acting on behalf of counsel to &ldquo;communicate with witnesses, potential clients, and clients in action(s) against Nevsun&rdquo;. Prior to Nevsun's application, the plaintiffs had maintained that Ms. Chryum was an unbiased and independent translator and interpreter. When Nevsun raised concerns with her role and her objectivity and impartiality, the plaintiffs rejected those concerns, but did not assert that Ms. Chryum was an agent of counsel and did not disclose her agreement to act as an agent of counsel.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>AMB Tab 13Q and 13R, Affidavit of Roxanne Dhanpaul #8, filed December 19, 2018, Exhibit &ldquo;Q&rdquo;, pp. 434&ndash;436; Exhibit &ldquo;R&rdquo;, pp. 438&ndash;440.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> On the waiver application, Nevsun argued the plaintiffs had not established that the communications with Ms. Chryum that were subject of objections on discovery were privileged.</P>
<P>12. During the hearing of Nevsun's application, counsel for the plaintiffs advised that the Reply filed in the Araya action erroneously pleaded postponement until the date of filing of the Notice of Civil Claim: November 20, 2014. Counsel advised the court that the plaintiffs would be applying to amend that Reply. In response, counsel for Nevsun alleged that this admission amounted to a further waiver.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>AMB Tab 1, Reasons, paras. 91&ndash;95.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>13. In the judgment sought to be appealed, Abrioux J. noted that the parties &ldquo;essentially agreed on the law&rdquo;, and that the plaintiffs admitted that &ldquo;privilege has been waived&rdquo;. The issue was the scope of the waiver. Abrioux J. agreed that the plaintiffs' plea of postponement put their reliance on legal advice at issue from the accrual of the claim to the date of the &ldquo;paradigm shift&rdquo; or date where they were able to receive advice to &ldquo;ascertain and assess&rdquo; their rights, which he found to include the first meeting with Canadian counsel.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>AMB Tab 1, Reasons, paras. 69&ndash;71, 77&ndash;80, 85&ndash;90.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Abrioux J. agreed that the plaintiffs' application to amend the Reply in the Araya action and Nevsun's further consequential waiver application should be heard expeditiously and set a schedule for the filing of materials.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>AMB Tab 1, Reasons, paras. 91&ndash;95.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Finally, Abrioux J. adjourned Nevsun's application for a determination of objections at discovery, but found that the particulars of Ms. Chryum's retainer should be disclosed to assist in delineating her precise role while acting as an alleged third party agent for counsel, and as potentially relevant to Nevsun's allegations of bias arising from her translator and interpreter functions.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>AMB Tab 1, Reasons, paras. 101&ndash;111.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The parties subsequently filed materials in connection with the plaintiffs' amendment application and Nevsun's further waiver application in the Araya action. Nevsun's further waiver application was heard on February 19, 2019.</P></BLOCK2></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="II">PART II: STATEMENT OF THE POINTS IN ISSUE</TI>
<P>14. The issues are (a) whether leave to appeal of the order of Abrioux J. is required; (b) if leave is required, whether leave should be granted; and (c) if leave is granted, the terms on which the order should be stayed.</P></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="III">PART III: ARGUMENT</TI>
<P>15. Abrioux J.'s order is a &ldquo;limited appeal order&rdquo; under the <EM>Court of Appeal Rules</EM>. That rule provides that an order granting or refusing relief under Part 7 of the <EM>SCCR</EM> is a limited appeal order. The declaration was sought because of the state of the plaintiffs' listing of privileged documents; the fact the ruling was expressed as a declaration does not affect the substance of the order. Abrioux J.'s order confirms that the plaintiffs have waived privilege and requires the plaintiffs to produce documents and answer questions on discovery. These orders arise in the discovery process and fall squarely within Part 7 of the <EM>SCCR</EM>.</P>
<P>16. Contrary to the plaintiffs' submissions, there is no basis to distinguish the decision of Justice Goepel in <CASEREF><SOC>Do Process LP v. Infokey Software Inc.</SOC></CASEREF><FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Do Process LP v. Infokey Software Inc.</SOC><CITE>2014 BCCA 470</CITE><PARANUM>9&ndash;11</PARANUM><DECIDER>Goepel J.A.</DECIDER><COURTJUR>in Chambers</COURTJUR></CASEREF>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> on the ground that the judgment here does not expressly state the jurisdictional basis for the order. In <CASEREF><SOC>H.M.B. Holdings Limited v. Replay Resorts Inc.</SOC></CASEREF>,<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>H.M.B. Holdings Limited v. Replay Resorts Inc.</SOC><CITE>2018 BCCA 8</CITE><PARANUM>12</PARANUM><DECIDER>Tysoe J.A.</DECIDER><COURTJUR>in Chambers</COURTJUR></CASEREF>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Justice Tysoe specifically considered himself obliged to follow <EM>Do Process</EM> in circumstances where the notice of application did not specifically rely on Rule 7-1 of the <EM>SCCR</EM>. Leave is required.</P>
<BLOCK2><TI>Leave to Appeal Should Not be Granted</TI>
<P>17. The factors to consider on a leave application are set out at paragraphs 22-23 of the plaintiffs' memorandum of argument.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Goldman, Sachs &amp; Co. v. Sessions et al.</SOC><CITE>2000 BCCA 326</CITE><DECIDER>Saunders J.A.</DECIDER><COURTJUR>in Chambers</COURTJUR></CASEREF>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The plaintiffs have failed to satisfy the test for leave to appeal. It is not in the interests of justice to grant leave.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>The Proposed Grounds of Appeal do not have Merit</TI>
<P>18. The proposed appeal has no prospect of success. The plaintiffs do not identify an extricable question of law or allege an &ldquo;erroneous assumption about the law&rdquo; in Abrioux J.'s application of the facts to the law.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Mayer v. Mayer</SOC><CITE>2012 BCCA 77</CITE><PARANUM>188</PARANUM></CASEREF>; <CASEREF><SOC>Housen v. Nikolaisen</SOC><CITE>2002 SCC 33</CITE><PARANUM>36</PARANUM></CASEREF>. <CASEREF><SOC>Do Process LP v. Infokey Software Inc.</SOC><CITE>2015 BCCA 52</CITE><PARANUM>21-22</PARANUM></CASEREF> (&ldquo;<BOLD><EM>Do Process</EM></BOLD>&rdquo;).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> There was no dispute below on the principles governing waiver of privilege.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Soprema Inc. v. Wolrige Mahon LLP</SOC><CITE>2016 BCCA 471</CITE><PARANUM>22, 44, 49</PARANUM></CASEREF> (&ldquo;<BOLD><EM>Soprema</EM></BOLD>&rdquo;); <CASEREF><SOC>H.M.B. Holdings Limited v. Replay Resorts Inc.</SOC><CITE>2018 BCCA 263</CITE><PARANUM>42&ndash;46</PARANUM></CASEREF> (&ldquo;<BOLD><EM>HMB</EM></BOLD>&rdquo;)</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The plaintiffs admitted that there was a waiver of privilege; the only question was the extent of that waiver. The plaintiffs' appeal is nothing more than a challenge to Abrioux J.'s assessment and characterization of the meaning and effect of the pleadings in the context of the ongoing prosecution of this case, with which he is thoroughly familiar.</P>
<P>19. It was open to Abrioux J. to find that the words used in the Replies confirmed that the plaintiffs relied on the legal advice obtained in the first meeting to understand their rights, which later changed their actions. There is no basis for this Court to revisit the case management judge's assessment of the pleadings, the relevant background, and the interests of fairness to the parties.</P>
<P>20. The plaintiffs argue that the case management judge fell into error by citing a 2014 article by Jonathan de Vries for the proposition that a waiver based on postponement includes information relevant to the act of discovery itself.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>De Vries, &ldquo;Privilege and Limitations: The Impact of Raising the Discoverability of Claims on Solicitor-Client Privilege&rdquo;, (2014) 43 Advocates Quarterly 219&ndash;256 (&ldquo;<BOLD>De Vries</BOLD>&rdquo;).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Contrary to the plaintiffs' submission, the law in B.C. is entirely consistent with the proposition articulated in the de Vries article, that the temporal scope of waiver extends beyond the putative discovery date identified by the plaintiff, a proposition which this Court implicitly accepted in the <EM>Harry</EM> case.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Harry v. British Columbia</SOC><CITE>2002 BCCA 557</CITE><PARANUM>13&ndash;18</PARANUM></CASEREF> (&ldquo;<BOLD><EM>Harry</EM></BOLD>&rdquo;), <CASEREF><CASEHIST><CASEDISP>affirming</CASEDISP><CASEREF><CITE>2001 BCSC 1566</CITE></CASEREF></CASEHIST></CASEREF> (&ldquo;<BOLD><EM>Harry SC</EM></BOLD>).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> This makes sense. As pointed out by de Vries immediately before the passage quoted by Abrioux J., it is the plaintiff who selects the discovery date or period; as a matter of fairness, Nevsun should be entitled to test through discovery the validity of that date of alleged postponement, particularly where, as here, different periods of postponement are pleaded.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>De Vries, pp. 251&ndash;254.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>21. The plaintiffs' second proposed ground of appeal alleges that the judge's order on the scope of disclosure went beyond what was necessary to achieve a just result. The plaintiffs articulate no extricable error of law in this ground, other than to vaguely suggest the judge erred in his &ldquo;application of the principles of waiver of privilege&rdquo;. The judge was clearly alive to the nature of solicitor-client privilege, which he called &ldquo;virtually sacrosanct&rdquo;.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>AMB Tab 1, Reasons, para. 71.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> He assessed the interests of fairness in reaching a decision he considered just to both parties.</P>
<P>22. The plaintiffs' final ground of appeal, concerning disclosure of the terms of Ms. Chryum's retainer, also has no reasonable prospect of success.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Shooting Star Amusements Ltd. v. Prince George Agricultural and Historical Association</SOC><CITE>2009 BCCA 452</CITE><DECIDER>Newbury J.A.</DECIDER><COURTJUR>in Chambers</COURTJUR></CASEREF>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The context here is important. Nevsun sought determinations on certain objections made by plaintiffs' counsel in the course of examinations. Abrioux J. adjourned the relief concerning those objections, as they are likely addressed by the waiver order, but ordered disclosure of Ms. Chryum's agreement&mdash;which the plaintiffs themselves raised and on which they relied, without disclosing it or its terms&mdash;because the record did not support the plaintiffs' assertion of privilege over her communications with the plaintiffs. In other words, this ground of appeal does not give rise to any legal issue about waiver. Given Ms. Chryum's dual role, production of the terms of her retainer is necessary to assess the validity of the plaintiffs' objections. There is no basis for this Court to interfere with the case management judge's order on this point.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>The Points Raised on Appeal are not of Significance to the Practice</TI>
<P>23. The points raised on this proposed appeal are not of significance to the practice. The issues on the proposed appeal do not require clarification, are well-settled, and have been addressed recently by this Court. The legal principles were not in dispute in the Court below, and the orders turn on particular facts and pleadings in this unusual case. Appeals from orders that are specific to the action and specific to particular procedural histories of the parties will not be of importance to the practice.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Gichuru v. Law Society of British Columbia</SOC><CITE>2012 BCCA 159</CITE><PARANUM>20</PARANUM><DECIDER>Bennett J.A.</DECIDER><COURTJUR>in Chambers</COURTJUR></CASEREF> (&ldquo;<BOLD><EM>Gichuru</EM></BOLD>&rdquo;); <CASEREF><SOC>National Union Fire insurance Company of Pittsburgh v. Barry Turpin et al.</SOC><CITE>1997 CanLII 4054</CITE><PARANUM>27</PARANUM><COURTJUR>B.C.C.A.</COURTJUR></CASEREF> (Hinds J.A. in Chambers).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>24. The principles of implied waiver are well-established, and this Court has addressed the issue on at least five occasions since 2014.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Brown v. Clark Wilson LLP</SOC><CITE>2014 BCCA 185</CITE></CASEREF>; <EM>Do Process, Soprema</EM>; <CASEREF><SOC>British Columbia (Attorney General) v. Lee</SOC><CITE>2017 BCCA 219</CITE></CASEREF>; <EM>HMB</EM>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> This Court recently agreed with the conclusion of a justice that an appeal where one of the grounds was waiver of privilege was of no significance because that law was settled.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Albu v. The University of British Columbia</SOC><CITE>2018 BCCA 185</CITE><PARANUM>16</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The principles regarding waiver of privilege as a result of pleading postponement were also addressed by this Court in <EM>Harry</EM>,<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Harry</EM>, affirming <EM>Harry SC</EM>, para. 15; <CASEREF><SOC>Camosun College v. Levelton Engineering Ltd.</SOC><CITE>2014 BCSC 1190</CITE></CASEREF>; <CASEREF><SOC>Jack v. Canada</SOC><CITE>[2004] O.J. No. 3294</CITE><COURTJUR>Sup. Ct. J.</COURTJUR></CASEREF>; De Vries, pp. 252-253.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> and require no additional clarification because they are consistent with this Court's most recent pronouncements on waiver of privilege.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Soprema</EM>, para. 49; <EM>HMB</EM>, para. 46.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>25. An appeal relating to the order of Ms. Chyrum's retainer raises no point requiring clarification or of significance to the profession. The case management judge concluded that disclosure of the terms of her retainer would be of assistance in delineating her precise role. The proposed appeal on this issue engages nothing but the failure of the plaintiffs to establish privilege on the evidence before the judge.</P>
<P>26. In short, the substance of the proposed appeal concerns the application of settled principles of the law of privilege, in a proceeding that is complex and unique, both substantively and procedurally. An appeal would be of limited utility and any decision by this Court would be confined to the facts of this case.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Cooper v. Hobart et al.</SOC><CITE>1999 BCCA 231</CITE><DECIDER>Cumming J.A.</DECIDER><COURTJUR>in Chambers</COURTJUR></CASEREF>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>An Appeal will Unduly Hinder the Progress of the Action</TI>
<P>27. Leave should be refused where an appeal would delay the orderly preparation of the action for trial or result in an adjournment. Even if the appeal can be expedited, delay will affect the prosecution and defence of this case.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Gichuru</EM>, para. 23; <CASEREF><SOC>Wolsley Canada Inc. v. Emco Corporation</SOC><CITE>2008 BCCA 18</CITE><PARANUM>16</PARANUM><DECIDER>Prowse J.A.</DECIDER><COURTJUR>in Chambers</COURTJUR></CASEREF>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>28. Here, an appeal would necessarily interfere with ongoing proceedings in the Supreme Court. Nevsun would be forced to choose between adjourning overseas discoveries of the plaintiffs or proceeding without the benefit of the documents the judge found were necessary to evaluate the postponement allegations. The discoveries are part of a comprehensive case management plan choreographed by Abrioux J. Their scheduling, in turn, affects the timing of the Bellwether Application and could jeopardize preparations for the trial date, particularly with the large number of discoveries that remain to be completed after July 1, 2019. Many of the claims are dated,<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>The earliest claims date from 2005. The majority of the plaintiffs allege they left the Bisha Mine in 2010.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> and the already-significant evidentiary difficulties in this litigation will be exacerbated by delay. In these circumstances, permitting an interlocutory appeal on the issue of the scope of an admitted waiver of privilege would not be in the interests of justice.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>Stay of Proceedings Pending Determination of the Appeal</TI>
<P>29. If leave is granted, provided that the appeal is expedited, Nevsun agrees that there should be a stay of Abrioux J.'s order pending determination of the appeal.</P></BLOCK2></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="IV">PART IV: NATURE OF ORDER REQUESTED</TI>
<P>30. That the plaintiffs' application for leave to appeal from the order of Abrioux J. be dismissed with costs to Nevsun.</P>
<P>Date: March 7, 2019</P>
<P>For &ellip35;</P>
<P>Andrew Nathanson, Counsel for the Defendant Nevsun Resources Ltd.</P></BLOCK1>
